'\n| Laura Lee\n|\n| <ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|-\n| 1977\n| ''[[Death Game]]''\n| Agatha Jackson\n|\n| <ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|-\n| 1977\n| ''[[The Shadow of Chikara]]''\n| Drusilla Wilcox\n|\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.moriareviews.com/horror/shadow-of-chikara-1977.htm|title=Shadow of Chikara (1977)|date=March 9, 2010|publisher=|accessdate=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1977\n| ''[[The Gauntlet (film)|The Gauntlet]]''\n| Augustina 'Gus' Mally\n|\n| <ref name=\"Bradshaw\"/>\n|-\n| 1978\n| ''[[Every Which Way but Loose (film)|Every Which Way but Loose]]''\n| Lynn Halsey-Taylor\n|\n| <ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/obituaries/2018/12/14/sondra-locke-actress-appeared-clint-eastwood-hit-films-1970s/ Sandra Locke appeared with Clint Eastwood in hit films] Telegraph Retrieved December 18, 2018</ref>\n|-\n| 1979\n| ''Friendships, Secrets and Lies''\n| Jessie Dunne\n| TV movie\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1979/12/03/archives/tv-friendships-secrets-and-lies.html|title=TV: 'Friendships, Secrets and Lies'|first=John J.|last=O'Connor|date=December 3, 1979|publisher=|accessdate=December 18, 2018|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1980\n| ''[[Bronco Billy]]''\n| Antoinette Lily\n|Nominated\u2014[[Razzie Award for Worst Actress]]\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.svenskfilmdatabas.se/sv/item/?type=film&itemid=7745|title=Bronco Billy (1980) \u2013 Svensk Filmdatabas|publisher=|accessdate=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1980\n| ''[[Any Which Way You Can]]''\n| Lynn Halsey-Taylor\n|\n| <ref name=\"bbc.com\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-46564964|title=Actress Sondra Locke dies aged 74|date=December 14, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=December 18, 2018|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''Rosie: The Rosemary Clooney Story''\n| [[Rosemary Clooney]]\n| TV movie\n| <ref name=\"bbc.com\"/>\n|-\n| 1983\n| ''[[Sudden Impact]]''\n| Jennifer Spencer\n|\n| <ref name=\"bbc.com\"/>\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[Tales of the Unexpected (TV series)|Tales of the Unexpected]]''\n| Edna\n| Episode: \"[[List of Tales of the Unexpected episodes#Series Seven|Bird of Prey]]\"\n| <ref name=\"bbc.com\"/>\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[Amazing Stories (1985 TV series)|Amazing Stories]]''\n| Vanessa Sullivan\n| Episode: \"Vanessa in the Garden\"\n| <ref name=\"bbc.com\"/>\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[Ratboy]]''\n| Nikki Morrison\n| Also director<br>Nominated\u2014[[Razzie Award for Worst Actress]]\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.comingsoon.net/horror/news/747256-interview-sondra-locke-talks-clint-eastwood-fate-ratboy|title=Interview: Sondra Locke Talks Clint Eastwood and the Fate of RATBOY|date=September 29, 2015|website=ComingSoon.net|accessdate=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''The Prophet's Game''\n| Adele Highsmith (adult)\n|\n| <ref name=\"people.com\">{{cite web |url=https://people.com/movies/actress-sondra-locke-dead-74/|title=Actress and Director Sondra Locke, Clint Eastwood's Former Girlfriend of 14 Years, Dies at 74|website=PEOPLE.com|accessdate=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1999\n| ''Clean and Narrow''\n| Betsy Brand\n|\n| <ref name=\"people.com\"/>\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Ray Meets Helen]]''\n| Helen\n| Final film role\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/keith-carradine-sondra-locke-ray-meets-helen-release-1202733026/|title=Film News Roundup: Keith Carradine-Sondra Locke's 'Ray Meets Helen' Gets Release|first1=Dave|last1=McNary|date=March 22, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===As director===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! class=\"unsortable\"| {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[Ratboy]]''\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://thewandrinstar.wordpress.com/2013/11/20/sondra-lockes-ratboy-a-modern-day-fairy-tale-en/|title=Sondra Locke's Ratboy: A modern day fairy tale|first=David|last=Furtado|date=November 20, 2013|publisher=|accessdate=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1990\n| ''[[Impulse (1990 film)|Impulse]]''\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/dec/14/sondra-locke-obituary|title=Sondra Locke obituary|first=Ryan|last=Gilbey|date=December 14, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=December 17, 2018|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''Death in Small Doses''\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://letterboxd.com/film/death-in-small-doses-1995/|title=Death in Small Doses (1995)|publisher=|accessdate=December 18, 2018|via=letterboxd.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[Trading Favors]]''\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/actress-director-sondra-locke-clint-021743085.html|title=Actress and Director Sondra Locke, Clint Eastwood's Former Girlfriend of 14 Years, Dies at 74|website=www.yahoo.com|accessdate=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Stage==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Show\n! Role\n! Location\n! {{Tooltip|Ref(s)|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n| 1962\n| ''[[Life with Father]]''\n| Mary Wickes\n| Tucker Theater, Murfreesboro, Tennessee\n|<ref name=\"DNJ 11-2-62\"/>\n|-\n| 1963\n| ''[[The Crucible]]''\n| Mary Warren\n| Tucker Theater, Murfreesboro, Tennessee\n|<ref name=\"DNJ 2-24-63\"/>\n|-\n| 1964\n| ''Life with Mother''\n| N/A\n| Belcourt Playhouse, Nashville, Tennessee\n|<ref>{{cite news|title=Several Days With the Days|newspaper=[[The Nashville Tennessean]]|date=February 16, 1964|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/111970652}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1964\n| ''[[The Innocents (play)|The Innocents]]''\n| Flora\n| Circle Theater, Nashville Tennessee\n|<ref>{{cite news|title=Shivers Missing in 'The Innocents'|newspaper=[[The Nashville Tennessean]]|date=June 18, 1964|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/111607043}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1964\n| ''A Thousand Clowns''\n| Dr. Sandra Markowitz\n| Circle Theater, Nashville, Tennessee\n|<ref>{{cite news|title=Erwin Has Rare Aplomb; Poise Brings Applause|newspaper=[[The Nashville Tennessean]]|date=August 20, 1964|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/112073032}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1965\n| ''[[Night of the Iguana]]''\n| Charlotte Goodall\n| Circle Theater, Nashville, Tennessee\n|<ref name=\"Tennessean 9-19-65\"/>\n|-\n| 1965\n| ''[[Oh Dad, Poor Dad, Mamma's Hung You in the Closet and I'm Feelin' So Sad]]''\n| Rosalie\n| Circle Theater, Nashville, Tennessee\n|<ref>{{cite news|title=Theater To Hold Tryouts|newspaper=[[The Nashville Tennessean]]|date=October 17, 1965|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/112090155}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1965\n| ''[[The Glass Menagerie]]''\n| Laura Wingfield\n| Circle Theater, Nashville, Tennessee\n|<ref>{{cite news|title='Menagerie' Opens|newspaper=[[The Nashville Tennessean]]|date=November 21, 1965|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/111833460}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1967\n| ''[[Tiger at the Gates]]''\n| Helen of Troy\n| Vanderbilt Theatre, Nashville, Tennessee\n|<ref>{{cite news|title='Tiger at the Gates' At Vanderbuilt Theater|newspaper=[[The Nashville Tennessean]]|date=January 20, 1967|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/113221744}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{notelist|60em}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Film|Television}}\n*[[List of American film actresses]]\n*[[List of female film and television directors]]\n*[[List of Middle Tennessee State University people]]\n*[[List of people from Los Angeles]]\n*[[List of people from Tennessee]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name}}\n*{{TCMDb name}}\n*{{Worldcat id|lccn-n93-89860}}\n\n{{Clint Eastwood|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Locke, Sondra}}\n[[Category:Actresses from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:American autobiographers]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American women film directors]]\n[[Category:American women non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Burials at Westwood Village Memorial Park Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Deaths from bone cancer]]\n[[Category:Deaths from breast cancer]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in California]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Middle Tennessee State University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Madison County, Alabama]]\n[[Category:People from Shelbyville, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Women autobiographers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Writers from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century American biographers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American biographers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|American actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = Sondra Locke\n| image           = Sondra Locke The Gondola 1974.jpg\n| caption         = Sondra Locke in ''The Gondola'' (1973) <!--Despite name of photo, \"The Gondola\" was broadcast in 1973-->\n| birth_name      = Sandra Louise Smith\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date|1944|05|28}}\n| birth_place     = [[Madison County, Alabama|Madison County]], [[Alabama]], U.S.\n| death_date      = {{Death date and age|2018|11|03|1944|5|28}}\n| death_place     = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| nationality     = [[United States|American]]\n| occupation      = {{flatlist|\n*Actress\n*director\n}}\n| yearsactive     = 1962\u20131999, 2016\n| spouse          = {{marriage|Gordon Anderson|1967|2018|end=her death}}\n| domesticpartner = [[Clint Eastwood]] (1975\u20131989)<br>Scott Cunneen (1990\u2013?)\n| website         = \n| signature       = Sondra Locke autograph signature.jpg\n}}\n\n'''Sandra Louise Anderson''' (n\u00e9e '''Smith'''; May 28, 1944 \u2013 November 3, 2018), professionally known as '''Sondra Locke''', was an American actress and director. She made her film debut in 1968 in ''[[The Heart Is a Lonely Hunter (film)|The Heart Is a Lonely Hunter]]'', for which she was nominated for an [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress]]. She went on to star in such films as ''[[Willard (1971 film)|Willard]]'', ''[[The Outlaw Josey Wales]]'', ''[[The Gauntlet (film)|The Gauntlet]]'', ''[[Every Which Way but Loose (film)|Every Which Way but Loose]]'', ''[[Bronco Billy]]'', ''[[Any Which Way You Can]]'' and ''[[Sudden Impact]]''. She worked often with [[Clint Eastwood]], who was her companion for 14 years. She also directed four films, notably ''[[Impulse (1990 film)|Impulse]]''. Locke's autobiography, ''The Good, the Bad, and the Very Ugly{{spaced ndash}} A Hollywood Journey'', was published in 1997.\n\n==Background, early life and education==\n\nSandra Louise Smith was born on May 28, 1944,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Slaughter|first=Sylvia|title=Sondra vs. Clint in palimony suit|journal=The Tennessean|date=May 28, 1989|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/113567847/|quote=Don Locke loves his sister. He misses her, and he regrets the fact that his three daughters don't have any knowledge of Sondra other than what they see on TV or in print or hear from gossipmongers. 'Sondra's not this kind of bad character,' he says. 'Maybe she's changed, but she was my big sister who used to play baseball with me. Sondra's gonna be 45 May 28 ...' Locke's publicist claims Sondra will be 42 today.}}</ref><ref>Varying sources have cited 1947 as her year of birth; however, [http://search.ancestry.com/iexec?htx=View&r=an&dbid=1169&iid=VRMUSATN1780_026539-00431&fn=Sondra+Louise&ln=Locke&st=r&ssrc=&pid=5149354 her marriage license] and [https://www.intelius.com/search/people/Sondra-L-Anderson/Los%20angeles-CA her entry on Intelius (under her legal name, Sondra Anderson)] establish the year as 1944.</ref> the daughter of [[New York City]] native Raymond Smith, then serving in the military, and Pauline Bayne, a pencil factory worker from [[Huntsville, Alabama]]. Her parents separated before her birth.<ref name=\"Furtado 8-31-13\">{{cite web |url=https://thewandrinstar.wordpress.com/2013/08/31/sondra-lockes-the-good-the-bad-and-the-very-ugly-the-woman-with-a-name-en/|title=Sondra Locke's The Good, the Bad, and the Very Ugly: The Woman with a Name|first=David|last=Furtado|date=August 31, 2013|publisher=Wand'rin' Star}}</ref> In her autobiography, Locke noted that \"Although Momma would not admit it, I knew Mr. Smith never married my mother.\"<ref name=\"autobio\">{{cite book|last=Locke|first=Sondra|title= The Good, the Bad, and the Very Ugly \u2013 A Hollywood Journey|publisher= [[William Morrow and Company]]|year= 1997|isbn=068815462X}}</ref> She had a maternal half-brother, Donald (born April 26, 1946) from Bayne's subsequent brief marriage to William B. Elkins.<ref>[http://www.genlookups.com/al_marriages/al-madison-brides29.htm Madison County, Alabama Brides - Page 29]</ref> When Bayne married Alfred Locke in 1948, Sandra and Donald adopted his surname.<ref>[http://files.usgwarchives.net/ga/walker/vitals/marriages/grlyt.txt WALKER COUNTY, GA - VITAL RECORDS  MARRIAGES]</ref> She grew up in [[Shelbyville, Tennessee]], where her stepfather owned a construction company;<ref name=\"Armstrong\">{{cite news|url=https://people.com/archive/cover-story-taking-up-the-gauntlet-vol-9-no-6/|title=Taking Up ''The Gauntlet''|first=Lois|last=Armstrong}} ''People'', February 13, 1978.</ref> the family later moved to nearby [[Wartrace, Tennessee|Wartrace]].<ref name=\"DNJ 11-2-62\">{{cite news|title=MTSC Presents|newspaper=[[The Daily News Journal]]|date=November 2, 1962|page=7|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/367622358}}</ref> Self-described as ambitious<ref>\"Sondra un-Lockes Film Golden Gates\". Dick Kleiner, ''Philadelphia Daily News'', October 9, 1968</ref> and independent-minded,<ref>\"Sondra Relates to True Self\". Lydia Lane, ''Los Angeles Times'', January 3, 1971</ref> Locke started working part-time at age 16, drove her own car, and had a telephone installed in her bedroom.<ref name=\"autobio\"/>\n\n[[File:Locke HS Yearbook.jpg|thumb|upright|right|Locke's yearbook photo, 1960]]\n\nLocke was a cheerleader and class valedictorian in junior high.<ref name=\"autobio\"/> From 1958, she attended [[Bedford County Schools|Shelbyville Central High School]], where she was again valedictorian and voted \"Duchess of Studiousness\" by classmates.<ref name=\"Slaughter\">{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/113567847/|title=Sondra vs. Clint in palimony suit|newspaper=The Tennessean|date=May 28, 1989}}</ref> She also played on the girls' basketball team, served as PTSA representative and was president of the French club.<ref>[https://www.classmates.com/yearbooks/Shelbyville-Central-High-School/4182770392 1959 Shelbyville Central High School Yearbook - Classmates]</ref><ref>[https://www.classmates.com/yearbooks/Shelbyville-Central-High-School/1000251503 1960 Shelbyville Central High School Yearbook - Classmates]</ref><ref>[https://www.classmates.com/yearbooks/Shelbyville-Central-High-School/4182758984 1961 Shelbyville Central High School Yearbook - Classmates]</ref><ref>[https://www.classmates.com/yearbooks/Central-High-School/19692 1962 Central High School Yearbook - Classmates]</ref> Regardless, she wasn't considered \"date material\" by the Lotharios of her class.<ref>\"Sondra Locke opens door to fame\". Marjory Adams, ''The Boston Globe'', August 27, 1968</ref> Following graduation in 1962, Locke enrolled at [[Middle Tennessee State University]] in [[Murfreesboro, Tennessee|Murfreesboro]] on a full scholarship.<ref name=\"autobio\"/> Majoring in drama,<ref name=\"DeGennaro\">{{cite news|url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/entertainment/2018/12/14/sondra-locke-dies-74-tennessee-native-oscar-nominated-actress-clint-eastwood/2309536002/|title=Oscar-nominated actress, Tennessee native Sondra Locke dies at 74|first=Nancy|last=DeGennaro}} December 14, 2018.</ref> she was a member of the [[Alpha Psi Omega]] honor society while at MTSU and appeared onstage in ''[[Life with Father]]'' and ''[[The Crucible]]''.<ref name=\"DNJ 11-2-62\"/><ref name=\"DNJ 2-24-63\">{{cite news|title=The Crucible Next College Production|newspaper=[[The Daily News Journal]]|date=February 24, 1963|page=15|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/367675380}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://content.mtsu.edu/cdm4/item_viewer.php?CISOROOT=%2Fmtsu1&CISOPTR=1540&CISOBOX=1&REC=6# |title=Sondra Locke in The Crucible: MTSU theater production, 1963 |access-date=November 9, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120328001053/http://content.mtsu.edu/cdm4/item_viewer.php?CISOROOT=%2Fmtsu1&CISOPTR=1540&CISOBOX=1&REC=6# |archive-date=March 28, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> She dropped out after completing two semesters of study.<ref name=\"Parish\">{{cite book|author=James Robert Parish|title=The Hollywood Book of Breakups|year=2006|publisher=John Wiley & Sons, Inc.|isbn=1630262080}}</ref>\n\nIn or around 1963, Locke broke off contact with her family, concluding, \"It made no sense for any of us to spend our lives pretending to have relationships that did not really exist.\"<ref name=\"autobio\"/> She never sought out to meet her biological father, and did not attend the funerals of her mother (deceased 1997) or stepfather (deceased 2007), nor did she have anything to do with her brother, sister-in-law and three nieces.<ref name=\"Slaughter\"/><ref>{{cite news |first=David|last=Melson|title=Picturing the Past 160: Sondra Locke on TV|date= May 23, 2012|website=Times-Gazette|url=https://www.t-g.com/blogs/davidmelson/entry/47864}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://people.com/archive/cover-story-after-the-loving-counting-the-cost-vol-32-no-6|title=When Harry Left Sondra|date=7 August 1989|work=People}}</ref> Donald blamed Gordon Anderson \u2013 Locke's best friend since adolescence and future husband \u2013 for the rift, claiming Anderson had \"an almost hypnotic spell on her.\"<ref name=\"Slaughter\"/>\n\nLocke held a variety of jobs, including as a bookkeeper for [[Tyson Foods]] and secretary in a real-estate office.<ref name=\"autobio\"/> She worked in the promotions department for [[WSM-TV]] in [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]] for approximately three years,<ref name=\"Slaughter\"/><ref>[https://www.wsmv.com/oscar-nominated-actress-channel-alum-sondra-locke-dead-at/article_5c441e28-ff43-11e8-b1bf-03009c64ebe1.html Oscar-nominated actress, Channel 4 alumna Sondra Locke dead at 74] ''WSMV.com'', December 13, 2018</ref> and modeled for ''[[The Tennessean]]'' fashion page.<ref name=\"Tennessean 8-30-68\">{{cite news|first=Harry|last=Haun|title=Sandra of Shelbyville Becomes Sondra of the Cinema|newspaper=[[The Tennessean]]|date=August 30, 1968|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/112215685}}</ref> In 1966, the 22-year-old Locke appeared in a [[United Press International|UPI]] wire photo that showed her cavorting in new fallen snow.<ref>{{cite news|title=Snow Hits Tennessee|newspaper=The Daily Times-News|date=November 3, 1966|page=1|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/52800836}}</ref> Within one year of this exposure, she decided to pursue a career in film and changed the spelling of her first name to avoid being called Sandy.<ref name=\"Tennessean 8-30-68\"/>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Rise to prominence===\n\nIn July 1967, Locke competed with 590 other Southern actresses and dozens of New York hopefuls for the part of Mick Kelly in a big-screen adaptation of [[Carson McCullers]]' novel ''[[The Heart Is a Lonely Hunter (film)|The Heart Is a Lonely Hunter]]'' opposite [[Alan Arkin]].<ref name=\"Tennessean 8-15-67\">{{cite news|author=Clara Hieronymus|title=Nashville Actress Gets Starring Movie Role|newspaper=The Tennessean|date=August 15, 1967|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/112143819}}</ref>{{efn|After-the-fact publicity claimed that 2,000 actresses tried out for the role.<ref>{{cite news|first=Linda|last=Loftus|title=Meeting Sondra Locke Was Groovy!|newspaper=[[The Cincinnati Enquirer]]|date=August 10, 1968|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/101421206/}}</ref>}} Previously, she had acted in television commercials and starred in theater productions for Circle Players Inc.<ref name=\"Slaughter\"/> For the ''Heart'' audition, then-fianc\u00e9 Gordon Anderson gave his bride a so-called Hollywood makeover: he bound her bosom,<ref name=\"Oppenheimer\">Peer J. Oppenheimer (November 24, 1968). [https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1774&dat=19681124&id=C-weAAAAIBAJ&sjid=4mUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4508,7092287&hl=en Sondra Locke\u2013 They Call Her 'The Beautiful Fake' : A selfless husband with a flair for fooling catapulted this shy officeworker to overnight stardom]. ''Sarasota Herald-Tribune''</ref> bleached her eyebrows<ref name=\"autobio\"/> and carefully fixed her hair, makeup and outfit so as to create a more [[gamine]] appearance.<ref>[https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/376659762/ New face in the movie world] ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'', August 12, 1968. Vol. 122, Iss. 225, Section 2, p. 6</ref> They also lied about her age, shaving off six years to seem younger<ref>[https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/sondra-locke-obituary-c0fqztgr5 Sondra Locke obituary] ''[[The Times]]'', December 15, 2018</ref> \u2013 a pretense Locke would keep up for the rest of her career.{{efn|In the 1960s, ''[[The Billings Gazette]]''<ref>{{cite journal|title=People Etc.|journal=The Billings Gazette|date=May 25, 1969|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/409481756|quote=Sweet little Sondra is actually 25 years old and married. Because of the movie, people think she's about 13, so she's now considering offers to do a nude layout for a magazine to prove she's no kid, and pave the way for adult roles.}}</ref> and ''[[The Nashville Tennessean]]''<ref name=\"Tennessean 12-24-67\">{{cite journal|last=Hieronymus|first=Clara|title=Nashvillians in the Times|journal=The Tennessean|date=December 24, 1967|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/113239153|quote=The spelling of her name has been changed to \"Sondra,\" her age lowered to 17 years for publicity purposes, and her residence in Nashville, where she was employed by WSM, wiped out.}}</ref> outed Locke for lying about her age, but it took decades for syndicated publications to catch on, and most sources would continue to use the incorrect birth year(s).<ref name=\"nndb\">[https://www.nndb.com/people/790/000024718/ Sondra Locke] ''[[Notable Names Database]]''</ref> Locke admitted in ''The Good, the Bad & the Very Ugly'' that she lied about her age early in her career, but claimed to have knocked only three years off, rather than six. In one of her final interviews, conducted in 2015 for ''[[The Projection Booth]]'' podcast, Locke said that she \"was just graduating high school\" when she made ''The Heart Is a Lonely Hunter'' when she was in fact in her mid-20s.<ref name=\"podcast1\">{{cite podcast | host=White, Mike | date=January 16, 2016 | title=Special Report: ''Death Game'' / ''Knock Knock'' | others=Interviews with Larry Spiegel, Sondra Locke, and [[David Worth (cinematographer)|David Worth]] | website=[[The Projection Booth]] | url=http://projection-booth.blogspot.com/2016/01/special-report-death-game-knock-knock.html}}</ref> In addition to the lie about her age, an international press release from 1967 omits Locke's time at MTSU as well as her residence in Nashville, where she had moved in 1963 after dropping out of college.<ref name=\"Tennessean 12-24-67\"/><ref>\"Cinderella Story Of Young Actress\". ''Montreal Gazette'', September 19, 1967</ref>}} After three auditions, she was cast in the role.<ref name=\"Tennessean 8-15-67\"/>\n\nThe film came out in the summer of 1968 to critical acclaim.<ref>\"Sondra Takes a Film by Storm\". ''The Sydney Morning Herald'', August 4, 1968</ref> Locke's performance garnered her an [[Academy Award]] nomination, as well as a pair of [[Golden Globe]] nominations for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Motion Picture|Best Supporting Actress]] and [[Golden Globe Award for New Star of the Year&nbsp;\u2013 Actress|Most Promising Newcomer]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Winners & Nominees: Best Performance by an Actress in a Supporting Role in any Motion Picture 1969|url=https://www.goldenglobes.com/winners-nominees/best-performance-actress-supporting-role-any-motion-picture/all-years#year-1969|website=GoldenGlobes.com|publisher=[[Golden Globe Award]]s|access-date=18 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1969|title=Oscar Ceremony 1969 (Actress In A Supporting Role)|website=Oscars.org|publisher=[[Academy Awards]]|access-date=18 August 2018}}</ref> She also won \"Most Promising New Star of the Year\" at the Show-A-Rama film exhibitor convention.<ref>{{cite news|author=Harrison Carroll|title=Behind the Scenes in Hollywood|newspaper=The Advocate-Messenger|date=March 12, 1969|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/143275609}}</ref> Although her salary for the film was reported in newspapers as $15,000, she later claimed it was less than one-third that amount.<ref name=\"autobio\"/>\n\n===Commercial ups and downs, missed roles, TV work===\n\nHoping to shed the Plain Jane image she accentuated in her screen debut, in January 1969 Locke posed for a semi-nude pictorial by photographer Frank Bez,<ref>''Times Leader'', 4.1.69</ref> which was published in the December issue of ''[[Playboy]]''.<ref name=\"Playboy\">\"Sex Stars of 1969'\". Arthur Knight and Hollis Alpert, ''Playboy'', Vol. 16, Iss. 12</ref> The ''Playboy'' layout established Locke's status as a [[sex symbol]], and the images were recycled in other men's magazines as her fame increased. Nearly three decades later, Locke said she still got those photos in fan mail for her autograph.<ref name=\"autobio\"/>\n\n[[File:David carradine sondra locke kung fu 1974.JPG|thumb|left|With [[David Carradine]] in ''[[Kung Fu (TV series)|Kung Fu]]'', 1974]]\n\nHer next role was as Melisse in ''[[Cover Me Babe]]'' (1970), originally titled ''Run Shadow Run'',<ref>Harold Heffernan (August 14, 1969). [https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1144&dat=19690814&id=d9weAAAAIBAJ&sjid=OVAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7253,5211235&hl=en Sondra Valuable Behind the Scene]. ''[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]''.</ref> opposite [[Robert Forster]]. She made it as part of a $150,000 three-picture deal with [[20th Century Fox]], and was compensated for the other two which never came to fruition.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://filmmakeriq.com/dailies/may-28-1944-sondra-locke-was-born/|title=May 28, 1944 Sondra Locke was born |date= May 28, 2019|publisher= FilmmakerIQ.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Abe|last=Greenberg|title=Hard Work vs. Jinx, or The Luck of Sondra Locke|newspaper=Valley Times from North Hollywood|date=June 11, 1969|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/580656861}}</ref> It was announced that she would play the lead in ''Lovemakers'' \u2013 a film adaptation of [[Robert Nathan]]'s novel ''The Color of Evening'' \u2013 but no movie resulted.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sondra Set for 'Lovemakers'|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|date=March 3, 1969|page=72|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/383073726}}</ref><ref>''Lansing State Journal'', 1.11.70</ref> Locke was offered [[Barbara Hershey]]'s role in ''[[Last Summer]]'' (1969), but her agent turned it down without telling her.<ref>{{cite book|author=Eila Mell|title=Casting Might-Have-Beens: A Film by Film Directory of Actors Considered for Roles Given to Others|year=2013|publisher=McFarland & Company|isbn=978-1476609768|page=142}}</ref> Shortly afterwards she passed on the lead in ''[[My Sweet Charlie]]'' (1970), which won an [[Emmy]] for its eventual star [[Patty Duke]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Harry Haun|title=Charade for Hollywood|newspaper=The Tennessean|date=May 16, 1971|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/112817921}}</ref>\n\nIn 1971, Locke co-starred with [[Bruce Davison]] and [[Ernest Borgnine]] in the psychological thriller ''[[Willard (1971 film)|Willard]]'', which became a surprise box office smash.<ref>Norma Lee Browning (August 4, 1971). [https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2457&dat=19710804&id=ZBo0AAAAIBAJ&sjid=zOAIAAAAIBAJ&pg=3582,1185644&hl=en What Makes a Box Office Hit?]. ''[[Bangor Daily News]]''.</ref> Locke felt overqualified for her role but did it as a favor to Davison,<ref name=\"podcast1\"/> who at the time was her unofficial paramour.<ref name=\"podcast2\">[https://gruesomemagazine.com/2017/06/26/willard-1971-episode-53-decades-horror-1970s/ (Podcast) Willard (1971) \u2014 Episode 53\u2014 Decades of Horror 1970s - Gruesome Magazine] June 26, 2017</ref> She was then featured in [[William A. Fraker]]'s underseen mystery ''[[A Reflection of Fear]]'' (1972) and held the title role in ''[[The Second Coming of Suzanne]]'' (1974), winner of three gold medals at the Atlanta Film Festival.<ref>Canadian Society of Cinematographers, ''Cinema Canada'', Issues 12-17, 1974</ref> Both films were shelved for two years before finally opening in arthouse cinemas, respectively, attracting little attention at first. Over time ''Suzanne'' has developed a [[cult following]],<ref name=\"autobio\"/><ref name=\"podcast1\"/> while ''Reflection'' is cited as an early example of [[media portrayals of transgender people]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.comingsoon.net/horror/news/748692-exclusive-interview-actress-sondra-locke-gender-bender-chiller-reflection-fear|title=Exclusive Interview: Actress Sondra Locke on Gender-Bender Chiller A REFLECTION OF FEAR|first=Lee|last=Gambin|date= February 15, 2016|publisher= ComingSoon.net}}</ref>{{efn|''A Reflection of Fear'' was not the first time Locke was considered to play a transsexual. In 1969, [[Christine Jorgensen]], the Bronx man who became a woman in 1953 after surgery and medical treatment in Denmark, mentioned Locke and [[Mia Farrow]] as contenders for a planned film version of her life. A fan of Locke's performance in ''The Heart Is a Lonely Hunter'', Jorgensen observed that \"In scenes where she didn't wear any makeup, Sondra looks very much like I did in my younger days. I think she might make an excellent choice.\"<ref>''Philadelphia Daily News'', 5.28.69</ref>}}\n\nIn 1973, Locke was attached to star in ''Terminal Circle''. \"It's a woman's role that comes along once in a lifetime,\" she said.<ref name=\"Miller 8-30-73\">\"The Actress Couldn't Resist\". Jeanne Miller, ''San Francisco Examiner'', August 30, 1973.</ref> The project was to be directed by Mal Karman and shot by cinematographer Robert Primes, who did camerawork for ''[[Gimme Shelter (1970 film)|Gimme Shelter]]'', but it was cancelled for lack of funds.<ref name=\"Miller 8-30-73\"/>\n\nLocke guested on top-rated television drama series during the first half of the 1970s, including ''[[The F.B.I. (TV series)|The F.B.I.]]'', ''[[Cannon (TV series)|Cannon]]'', ''[[Barnaby Jones]]'' and ''[[Kung Fu (TV series)|Kung Fu]]''. Her agents advised her to stay away from TV, but she thought it was silly to sit around not working between movies.<ref>[https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/181104850 Actress says TV creates automatons] Will Jones, ''Star Tribune'', December 3, 1972</ref> In the 1972 ''[[Night Gallery]]'' episode \"A Feast of Blood\",<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nightgallery.net/night-gallery-episode-guide-season-two/|website=NightGallery.net|title=Rod Serling's Night Gallery: the Second Season; A Feast of Blood (NIGHT GALLERY #22 - original air date January 12, 1972)|publisher=[[Universal Television]]|date=2018}}</ref> she played the victim of a curse planted by [[Norman Lloyd]]; the recipient of a brooch that devoured her. Lloyd acted with Locke again in ''The Gondola'' (1973), a three-character teleplay co-starring [[Bo Hopkins]], and commended the actress for \"a beautiful performance \u2013 perhaps her best ever.\"<ref>{{cite book|author=Norman Lloyd|title=Stages: Norman Lloyd|year=1990|publisher=Directors Guild of America|isbn=0810822903|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/stagesnormanlloy00lloy}}</ref> [[Ron Harper (actor)|Ron Harper]], who worked with Locke on the short-lived 1974 show ''[[Planet of the Apes (TV series)|Planet of the Apes]]'', was even more effusive: \"After acting with her in a couple of scenes, there was something so feminine about her that I could picture myself easily falling for her ... She's one of those women who exudes femininity, and you just become so attracted to that.\"<ref>{{cite book|author=Tom Weaver|title=I Talked with a Zombie: Interviews with 23 Veterans of Horror and Sci-Fi Films and Television|year=2009|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0786452682|page=154}}</ref>\n\n===Films with Clint Eastwood===\n\nIn 1975, Locke took a supporting role in ''[[The Outlaw Josey Wales]]'' as the love interest of [[Clint Eastwood]]'s eponymous character.<ref>\"Eastwood co-star set\". ''Lansing State Journal'', October 28, 1975</ref> Locke said she chose the role for its exposure,<ref>\"A long time between breaks\". Jeanne Miller, ''San Francisco Examiner'', July 1, 1976</ref> following a run of unremarkable credits,<ref>\"Career Off to Great Start, and Then...\". Stanley Eichelbaum, ''San Francisco Examiner'', November 3, 1972</ref> and took a pay cut just to be in the film.<ref name=\"McGilligan\">{{cite book|author=Patrick McGilligan|title=Clint: The Life and Legend|year=1999|publisher=HarperCollins|isbn=000255528X}}</ref> Her salary for ''Josey Wales'' was $18,000 \u2013 less than half of what she'd earned for her previous job.<ref name=\"McGilligan\"/> The film was a big hit and revived Locke's career.<ref>[https://www.allmovie.com/artist/sondra-locke-p100009 Sondra Locke | Biography, Movie Highlights and Photos] Hal Erickson, ''[[AllMovie]]''</ref> She followed it up with a lead role alongside Eastwood in the popular action film ''[[The Gauntlet (film)|The Gauntlet]]'' (1977).<ref>\"Clint and Sondra A Big New Team?\". ''Asheville Citizen-Times'', December 2, 1977</ref> The duo replaced [[Steve McQueen]] and [[Barbra Streisand]], who bowed out from the production due to an apparent clash of egos.<ref>\"Eastwood getting a lock on Locke\". ''Independent Press-Telegram'', April 17, 1977</ref> Its pre-publicity touted Locke as \"the first actress ever to be in a Clint Eastwood movie and get equal billing on screen with the macho star.\"<ref>''New York Daily News'', 11.11.77</ref> Eastwood unblushingly predicted that she would win an Oscar for her performance.<ref>''Fort Lauderdale News'', 11.16.77</ref> Locke wasn't even nominated and received mixed reviews at best.\n\n[[File:Eastwood Locke The Gauntlet 1977.jpg|thumb|Eastwood and Locke in ''The Gauntlet'' (1977)]]\n\nOver the course of their decade-and-a-half-long personal relationship, Locke did not work in any capacity on any theatrical motion picture other than with Eastwood except for 1977's experimental horror western ''[[The Shadow of Chikara]]''.<ref name=\"Puig\">{{cite news |first=Claudia|last=Puig|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1989-05-08-ca-2546-story.html |title=In the Matter of Locke vs. Eastwood |publisher=Articles.latimes.com |date=May 8, 1989}}</ref> The home invasion film ''[[Death Game]]'' (1977), though released after they became an item, was actually shot in 1974.<ref>\"Local Angle\". ''Pittsburgh Post-Gazette.'' Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania. October 21, 1974. p. 12.</ref> \"Clint wanted me to work only with him,\" she said.<ref name=\"autobio\"/> \"He didn't like the idea of me being away from him.\"<ref name=\"E! 9-11-96\">{{cite web |url=http://www.eonline.com/news/33559/eastwood-s-ex-lover-says-he-torpedoed-her-career|title=Eastwood's Ex-Lover Says He Torpedoed Her Career |work=[[E! News]]|first=Marcus|last=Errico|date=September 11, 1996}}</ref>\n\nIn 1978, Locke and Eastwood appeared with an orangutan named Manis in that year's fourth highest-grossing film, ''[[Every Which Way but Loose (film)|Every Which Way but Loose]]''.<ref>[https://www.the-numbers.com/box-office-records/domestic/all-movies/cumulative/released-in-1978 Top 1978 Movies at the Domestic Box Office] ''The-Numbers''.</ref> She portrayed country singer Lynn Halsey-Taylor in the adventure-comedy. Its 1980 sequel, ''[[Any Which Way You Can]]'' \u2013 for which Locke earned a six-figure salary plus a share of the profits<ref name=\"McGilligan\"/> \u2013 was nearly as successful.<ref>[http://boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?yr=1980 1980 Yearly Box Office Results] [[Box Office Mojo]]</ref> She recorded several songs for the soundtracks of these films and was whispered to be shopping for a record deal at the time. Honing her musical skills, Locke performed live in concert with [[The Everly Brothers]], [[Eddie Rabbitt]] and [[Tom Jones (singer)|Tom Jones]].<ref>''Chicago Tribune'', 2.1.79</ref>\n\nDuring this period, Eastwood did a few movies that had no prominent female character for Locke to play. In the meantime, she accepted some television offers, co-starring with an all-female ensemble cast in ''Friendships, Secrets & Lies'' (1979) and portraying [[Big band]] era vocalist [[Rosemary Clooney]] in ''Rosie: The Rosemary Clooney Story'' (1982).<ref>''The Evening Sun'', 7.29.82</ref> While the biopic followed Clooney from age 17 to 40, Locke was 38 when she played the role.\n\nLocke starred as a bitter heiress who joins a traveling [[Wild West]] show in ''[[Bronco Billy]]'' (1980), her only film with Eastwood not to reach blockbuster status. She cited ''Bronco Billy'' and ''The Outlaw Josey Wales'' as her favorites of the movies they made together.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://henryswesternroundup.blogspot.com/2015/12/ridiculous-6-c-bar-reviewed-plus-josey.html|author=Henry C. Parke |title=Outlaw Josey Wales \u2013 Forty Years Later|date=December 15, 2015|work=Henry's Western Round-up}}</ref> The couple's final collaboration as performers was ''[[Sudden Impact]]'' (1983), the highest-grossing film in the ''[[Dirty Harry (film series)|Dirty Harry]]'' franchise,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/franchises/chart/?id=dirtyharry.htm |title=Dirty Harry Movies|accessdate=March 1, 2009 |website=[[Box Office Mojo]]}}</ref> in which Locke played an artist with her own code of vigilante justice. Her fee was a reported $350,000.<ref name=\"McGilligan\"/>\n\nLocke never appeared in a [[wide release]] after ''Sudden Impact''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.the-numbers.com/person/86870401-Sondra-Locke#tab=acting|title=Sondra Locke - Box Office |publisher= The-Numbers}}</ref> The film premiered five months before her 40th birthday, the customary cutoff age for leading ladies of the era. Locke announced plans to develop and star in a movie about [[Marie Antoinette]], but the project fell apart.<ref>{{cite news |first=Lou|last=Lumenick|title= DVD Extra: New 'Dirty Harry' Set Showcases \u2026 Sondra Locke |date= June 3, 2008|website=|url=https://nypost.com/2008/06/03/dvd-extra-new-dirty-harry-set-showcases-sondra-locke/}}</ref> Eastwood then directed Locke in a 1985 ''[[Amazing Stories]]'' episode titled \"Vanessa in the Garden\".\n\n===Directing===\n\nIn 1986, Locke made her feature directorial debut with ''[[Ratboy]]'', a fable about a youth who is half-rat, produced by Eastwood's company [[Malpaso Productions|Malpaso]].<ref>\"Sondra Locke tries other side of the camera\". ''The Greenville News'', September 28, 1985</ref>  When asked why she'd been absent from her longtime beau's recent star vehicles, Locke replied simply, \"I wasn't right for the roles.\"<ref>\"Locke Turns To 'Ratboy' To Escape Clint's Maze\". Roderick Mann, ''Los Angeles Times'', March 23, 1986</ref> ''Ratboy'' had limited distribution in the United States, where it was a critical and financial flop, but was well-received in Europe, with French newspaper ''[[Le Parisien]]'' calling it the highlight of the [[Deauville Film Festival]].<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/1987-02-15/entertainment/ca-3253_1_studio-trap 'Ratboy': Snared In The Studio Trap]. Pat. H. Broeske, ''Los Angeles Times''. February 15, 1987.</ref>\n\nConcentrating exclusively on directing from that point onward, Locke's second foray behind the camera was ''[[Impulse (1990 film)|Impulse]]'' (1990), starring [[Theresa Russell]] as a police officer on the vice squad who goes undercover as a prostitute. [[Siskel & Ebert]] gave the film \"two thumbs up\".<ref>[https://www.listal.com/list/siskel-ebert-1990-ratings Siskel and Ebert 1990 Ratings list]</ref> In a subsequent interview with [[Gene Siskel|Gene]], Locke said, \"If you love the craft of filmmaking as much as I do, it's hard to go back to acting after you've tasted the high of directing.\"<ref>{{cite news |first=Gene|last=Siskel|title=Sondra Locke's Step|date=May 6, 1990|website=|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1990-05-06-9002060768-story.html}}</ref>\n\nAfter a long interruption in her career due to personal and legal difficulties, Locke directed the made-for-television film ''Death in Small Doses'' (1995), based on a true story, and the independent feature ''[[Trading Favors]]'' (1997), starring [[Rosanna Arquette]].\n\n===Memoir and final projects===\n\nIn 1997, Locke's 371-page autobiography ''The Good, the Bad and the Very Ugly: A Hollywood Journey'' was published by [[William Morrow and Company]]. In it she called Eastwood \"a completely evil, manipulating, lying excuse for a man.\"<ref name=\"autobio\"/> Eastwood's lawyers sent a warning letter to the publisher, and although no slander charges arose, ''[[Entertainment Tonight]]'' canceled a scheduled interview with Locke.<ref name=\"Waxman\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1997/11/20/make-her-day/c88a1970-c896-48ba-b321-a63541d437b5|title=Make Her Day|author=Sharon Waxman|date=November 20, 1997|work=The Washington Post}}</ref> She was also bumped from ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]'' and, in her words, \"shut out of most venues to promote the book, in particular the networks.\"<ref name=\"Furtado 10-19-13\">{{cite web |url=https://thewandrinstar.wordpress.com/2013/10/19/exclusive-interview-with-sondra-locke-magic-in-films-and-the-real-world-en/|title=Exclusive Interview with Sondra Locke: Magic in films and the real world|first=David|last=Furtado|date=October 19, 2013|publisher=Wand'rin' Star}}</ref> The book received a rave and supportive review from ''[[New York Daily News]]'' writer [[Liz Smith (journalist)|Liz Smith]],<ref>\"Struggling Locke strikes back at Eastwood\". Liz Smith, ''The Baltimore Sun'', October 22, 1997</ref> while ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'''s Dana Kennedy dismissed the book as a \"peculiar, not terribly consequential, life story.\"<ref name=\"Kennedy\">{{cite web |url=https://ew.com/article/1997/10/31/book-review-good-bad-and-very-ugly/|first=Dana|last=Kennedy|title=Book Review: 'The Good, the Bad and the Very Ugly'|date=October 31, 1997|publisher=Entertainment Weekly}}</ref>\n\nLocke told a Spanish website that she'd been informed ''Entertainment Weekly'' originally planned to publish a positive review, but for reasons unclear, it was pulled and a negative review appeared instead.<ref name=\"Furtado 10-19-13\"/> ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]'', a monthly gay interest magazine, was set to do a big article on Locke's book, \"which was a natural because of Gordon being gay.\"<ref name=\"Furtado 10-19-13\"/> Suddenly and uncharacteristically, Eastwood gave ''The Advocate'' an interview, and they decided not to run both pieces; Locke insisted it was no coincidence.<ref name=\"Furtado 10-19-13\"/> She reflected in 2012, \"Clint has said so many bad things about me to the media since we split up, and he has so much more access and power to do that. He's said things that were hurtful to my character and hurtful to me professionally.\"<ref name=\"doco\">''L'album secret de Clint Eastwood''. Dir. {{ill|Pierre Maraval|fr|Pierre Maraval (historien)}}, 2012</ref> Locke was nonetheless grateful to have a platform at all, stating, \"It was a miracle that a major publisher took it.\"<ref name=\"Furtado 10-19-13\"/>\n\nAfter 13 years away from acting, Locke returned to the screen in 1999 with small roles in the straight-to-video films ''The Prophet's Game'' with [[Dennis Hopper]] and ''Clean and Narrow'' with [[Wings Hauser]]. In 2014, the media announced that Locke would serve as an executive producer on the [[Eli Roth]] film ''[[Knock Knock (2015 film)|Knock Knock]]'', starring [[Keanu Reeves]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Voltage taking Eli Roth's Knock Knock with Keanu Reeves to Cannes |first=Jeremy |last=Kay |newspaper=ScreenDaily |date=April 28, 2014 |url=http://www.screendaily.com/news/production/voltage-taking-knock-knock-to-cannes/5071058.article |location=Cannes}}</ref> She came out of retirement once more in 2016, shooting [[Alan Rudolph]]'s indie ''[[Ray Meets Helen]]'' with [[Keith Carradine]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/article/BWW-Interview-Keith-Carradine-on-the-New-Encores-Cast-Album-of-PAINT-YOUR-WAGON-20160603|title=BWW Interview: Keith Carradine on the New Encores! Cast Album of PAINT YOUR WAGON|author=Adrienne Onofri|date=June 3, 2016|work=BroadwayWorld}}</ref> The film was screened at Laemmle Music Hall on May 6, 2018, less than six months before Locke passed away.<ref>[https://blog.laemmle.com/2018/05/alan-rudolph-keith-carradine-sondra-locke-and-jennifer-tilly-in-person-at-the-music-hall-for-ray-meets-helen/ Alan Rudolph, Keith Carradine, Sondra Locke and Jennifer Tilly in Person at the Music Hall for RAY MEETS HELEN.] May 3, 2018</ref>\n\n==Philanthropy==\n\nIn 1992, Locke served as honorary chairwoman for the \"Starry, Starry Night\" silent auction in [[Costa Mesa, California]] to benefit Human Options, a shelter for victims of domestic violence. \"Being a woman I have great empathy for these women. I can understand how stranded they must feel, how hard it is to change one's life,\" Locke said.<ref>\"For Human Options, the Light Is Bright\". ''Los Angeles Times'', December 16, 1992</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\n===Mixed-orientation marriage===\n\nOn September 25, 1967,<ref name=\"Oppenheimer\"/> Locke married sculptor Gordon Leigh Anderson{{efn|Gordon Anderson went by the stage names 'C.B. Anderson'<ref name=\"Tennessean 9-19-65\">{{cite news|title='All Pure Pleasure,' Veteran Of Theater Flight Reports|newspaper=[[The Nashville Tennessean]]|date=September 19, 1965|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/111984017}}</ref> and 'Gordon Addison'<ref>[https://www.broadwayworld.com/people/Gordon-Addison/ Gordon Addison Broadway and Theatre Credits] ''[[Broadway World]]''</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=William|last=Glover|title=6 Characters in Search of Theme|newspaper=[[Oakland Tribune]]|date=June 25, 1966|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/476791444}}</ref> during a brief acting career before he married Locke.}} (born August 2, 1944 in [[Jonesboro, Arkansas]]) at the [[First Presbyterian Church (Nashville, Tennessee)|First Presbyterian Church]] in Nashville,<ref>{{cite news|author=|title=Ask Showcase|newspaper=The Tennessean|date=November 2, 1975|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/112093927}}</ref> one week after ''The Heart Is a Lonely Hunter'' commenced principal photography.<ref name=\"Tennessean 8-15-67\"/> She had known Anderson since 1956, when they met in seventh grade at Shelbyville Mills School.{{efn|In magazine interviews, Locke and Anderson would variously claim to have met when they were 10,<ref name=\"Armstrong\"/> 11<ref name=\"Oppenheimer\"/> or 12.<ref>''[[Look (American magazine)|Look]]'', 4.2.68</ref> Anderson, like his late wife, always lied about his age, thus contributing to the inconsistency.}} In early 1969, as Locke was flooded with script offers after her Oscar nomination, she and Anderson left Tennessee and moved into a condo in [[West Hollywood]].\n\nAccording to a 1989 [[affidavit]], the marriage was \"tantamount to sister and brother\" and they never [[consummation|consummated]] it.<ref name=\"Palm Beach Post\">{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=PBPB&p_theme=pbpb&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAF82D6894FA344&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |title=Locke Married? |newspaper= [[The Palm Beach Post]] |date=May 9, 1989}}</ref> Anderson is openly gay.<ref>\"Clint, Me and My Gay Husband: Sondra Locke Tells of Her Bizarre Love Life\". Kevin Smith, ''Daily Mail'', September 13, 1996</ref><ref name=\"Bradshaw\">{{cite news|last=Bradshaw|first=Peter|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/dec/14/sondra-locke-a-charismatic-performer-defined-by-a-toxic-relationship-with-clint-eastwood|title=Sondra Locke: a charismatic performer defined by a toxic relationship with Clint Eastwood|work=The Guardian|location=London|date=December 14, 2018|access-date=December 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title= Biography: Sondra Locke - TCM |work= [[Tcm.com]] |url= http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/person/115332%7C141343/Sondra-Locke/companions.html}}</ref><ref name=\"Hammond\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vanguardnewsnetwork.com/v1/2004b/InstaurationEastwood.htm|title=The Clintessential Eastwood|first=Judson|last=Hammond|date=April 1998|publisher=Instauration}}</ref><ref>\"[https://scholar.lib.vt.edu/VA-news/VA-Pilot/issues/1997/vp971126/11250106.htm Eastwood's Ex Tells All in Unflattering New Book]. Peggy Deans Earle, ''The Virginian-Pilot'', November 26, 1997</ref> Locke, testifying under oath to a jury, characterized her husband as being \"more like a sister to me\" and explained, \"It's funny the sort of cultural changes, but in those days males and females never lived together unless they were married.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1996-09-16/local/me-44434_1_eastwood-s-movies/2|title=Eastwood Unforgiven: Locke's Lawsuit Spins Saga of Love and Power in Hollywood|first=Ann W.|last=O'Neill|date=September 16, 1996|publisher=|accessdate=December 14, 2018|via=LA Times}}</ref> According to her death certificate, the two were still legally married when she died, and he was the person who reported her death.<ref name=\"Dalton\">{{cite news |first=Andrew|last=Dalton|title=Oscar-nominated actress Sondra Locke dies at 74|date=December 13, 2018|website=AP News}}</ref>\n\nAnderson is front and center in Locke's autobiography, but she doesn't elaborate on her reasons for marrying him beyond the following passage:\n\n{{bquote|However conventional or unconventional our marriage might turn out to be honestly did not concern me that much. I was very young, but I had come to feel that, for me, sex was the least important element in a relationship and the one thing that time had proven to me was that my love for Gordon came from such a deeply connected place that it transcended everything else.<ref name=\"autobio\"/>}}\n\n===Dalliances===\n\nGiven that Locke waited decades to confirm that her marriage was [[platonic love|platonic]], most of her actual romantic attachments went unpublicized. In the mid-1960s, she dated her supervisor at WSM-Channel 4's [[Public relations|PR]] department, Brad Crandall (1920\u20131973).<ref name=\"Nelson\">[https://www.facebook.com/nelsonperson/posts/10156861642964420 Alan Nelson - The Associated Press has reported that... | Facebook]</ref><ref>[https://www.facebook.com/groups/121957024614428/permalink/1566392453504204/ The Official Tennessee Radio Hall Of Fame Community Public Group | Facebook]</ref><ref>{{cite journal |date=April 8, 1967|title=Videotapers' Syndication $$ Whopper for Nashville |journal=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc. |volume=79 |issue=14 |pages=40 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DygEAAAAMBAJ}}</ref> Former colleagues at the station have insinuated posthumously that Locke was promoted to the department through [[nepotism]].<ref name=\"Nelson\"/> She started as secretary to Tom Griscom Jr. in local sales for WSM Radio.<ref name=\"Nelson\"/><ref>''The Nashville Tennessean'', 1.25.64</ref>\n\nGeorge Crook, a cameraman for WSM, squired Locke to Nashville society events including the 1965 [[hunt ball]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Hunt Ball To Climax Weekend|newspaper=[[The Nashville Tennessean]]|date=May 7, 1965|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/111821856}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Federation Dance Tonight|newspaper=[[The Nashville Tennessean]]|date=December 15, 1965|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/112130980}}</ref> He later got into local politics and was elected mayor of [[Belle Meade, Tennessee|Belle Meade]] in 2000. Locke was also rumored to have dated co-stars [[Bruce Davison]] (''Willard''), [[Paul Sand]] (''The Second Coming of Suzanne'') and [[Bo Hopkins]] (''Gondola''), as well as producer [[Hawk Koch]] and [[John F. Kennedy]]'s nephew [[Robert Shriver]].<ref name=\"podcast2\"/><ref>''Walter Scott's Personality Parade''. October 15, 1989.</ref><ref name=\"People 5-15-89\">{{cite web|url=https://people.com/archive/suing-clint-eastwood-sondra-locke-strikes-with-magnum-force-vol-31-no-19/|title=Suing Clint Eastwood, Sondra Locke Strikes with Magnum Force|first1=Joanne|last1=Kaufman|first2=Jacqueline|last2=Savaiano|date= May 15, 1989|work=People}}</ref>\n\nLocke alluded to these intervals as \"casually exploring for a romantic relationship,\" nothing that she had not fallen in love with any of the men. \"Love ... was not something to search out actively; it finds you, I believed.\"<ref name=\"autobio\"/>\n\n===Life with Eastwood===\n\n[[File:Josey Wales publicity.jpg|thumb|right|[[Chief Dan George]] with Locke and Eastwood at a barbecue in [[Santa Fe, New Mexico]] promoting ''The Outlaw Josey Wales'' (1976)]]\n\nLocke and actor/director [[Clint Eastwood]] entered a domestic partnership in October 1975.<ref name=\"Parish\"/> She first met Eastwood in 1972 when she unsuccessfully lobbied for the title role in his film ''[[Breezy]]'' (1973);<ref>{{cite book |last=O'Brien |first=Daniel |title=Clint Eastwood: Film-Maker |publisher=B. T. Batsford |year=1996 |isbn=0-7134-7839-X |location=London}}</ref> they became involved upon arrival at the shooting location of ''The Outlaw Josey Wales'' (1976) in [[Page, Arizona]].<ref name=\"Barnes\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/sondra-locke-dead-oscar-nominated-actress-was-74-1169048|title=Sondra Locke, Oscar-Nominated Actress for 'The Heart Is a Lonely Hunter,' Dies at 74|website=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=December 14, 2018}}</ref> \"It was just an immediate attraction between the two of us,\" Locke recalled in a 2012 documentary.<ref name=\"doco\"/> She revealed that they made love on their first date \"not once, but several times.\"<ref>[https://www.deseret.com/1998/1/5/19356125/locke-s-book-tells-the-good-the-bad-and-the-very-ugly Locke's book tells `The Good, the Bad and the Very Ugly'] ''Deseret News'', January 5, 1998.</ref> Locke had simultaneously been wooed by screenwriter [[Philip Kaufman]] but chose Eastwood over him.<ref name=\"Eliot\">{{cite book|author=Marc Eliot|title= American Rebel: The Life of Clint Eastwood|year=2009|publisher=Three Rivers Press|isbn=978-0307336897}}</ref> After wrapping the film in December 1975, Locke and Eastwood shuttled between his houses in [[Sherman Oaks]] and [[Carmel-by-the-Sea, California|Carmel]], as well as rented homes in [[San Francisco]] and [[Tiburon, California|Tiburon]].<ref name=\"McGilligan\"/> They eventually settled in [[Bel Air, Los Angeles|Bel-Air]].<ref name=\"Parish\"/>\n\nEastwood was married during the first several years of their relationship,<ref name=\"Young\">[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/the-good-the-bad-and-the-ugly-1259606.html The Good, the Bad and the Ugly] Young, Josh (May 4, 1997). ''The Independent''.</ref><ref>\"Eastwood won't wed girlfriend\". ''The San Bernardino County Sun'', September 8, 1979</ref> before their affair became public in 1978,<ref name=\"Parish\"/> but if anything his marriage was as big a sham as Locke's \u2013 he'd sired at least two publicly unacknowledged children outside the marriage<ref name=\"McGilligan\"/><ref>{{cite journal|title=Clint's Bombshell Secret \u2013 He Has Illegitimate Daughter & Grandson|first1=Mike|last1=Kerrigan|first2=Brian|last2=Williams|date= July 11, 1989|journal=National Enquirer}}</ref><ref>[https://www.insideedition.com/clint-eastwood-appears-public-his-secret-daughter-first-time-49254 Clint Eastwood Appears in Public With His Secret Daughter for the First Time] ''[[Inside Edition]]'' (December 14, 2018)</ref><ref name=\"Bergen\">{{cite news|url=https://pagesix.com/2018/12/27/the-wild-story-of-clint-eastwoods-eight-children/#1|title=The wild story of Clint Eastwood's eight children|first=Spencer|last=Bergen}} ''[[Page Six]]'' December 27, 2018.</ref> and confided he'd \"never been in love before.\"<ref name=\"autobio\"/><ref name=\"Miller\">{{cite news|url=https://www.inquisitr.com/5208766/sondra-locke-clint-eastwood-inside-their-tumultuous-hollywood-romance/|title=Sondra Locke & Clint Eastwood: Inside Their Rocky Hollywood Romance|first=Victoria|last=Miller}} December 14, 2018.</ref> Locke claimed Eastwood sang \"She Made Me Monogamous\" to her.<ref name=\"Young\"/><ref name=\"Miller\"/><ref>{{cite book|last=Radner|first=Hilary|title=The New Woman's Film: Femme-centric Movies for Smart Chicks|year=2017|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1317286486}}</ref> Eastwood's wife Maggie Johnson lived on a colossal estate in [[Pebble Beach]], where Eastwood rarely stayed,<ref name=\"autobio\"/> and he and Johnson were understood to have had an [[open marriage]] from the start.<ref>{{cite book|last=Eden|first=Barbara|title=Jeannie Out of the Bottle|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780307886941|url-access=registration|year=2011|publisher=Crown Archetype|isbn=978-0307886958}}</ref><ref name=\"Thompson\">{{cite book|author=Douglas Thompson|title= Clint Eastwood: Billion Dollar Man|year=2005|publisher=[[John Blake (journalist)|John Blake]]|isbn=1857825721}}</ref> \"I never knew I could love somebody so much, and feel so peaceful about it at the same time,\" Locke said he told her.<ref name=\"autobio\"/> Conversely, the media's running narrative was that Eastwood \"left\"<ref name=\"Bradshaw\"/> or \"walked out on\"<ref name=\"People 5-15-89\"/> his wife for Locke as opposed to simply giving up the facade. Locke resented being labeled as an affair and made to feel sleazy as if she'd \"stolen\" a married man, but did not refute it.<ref name=\"autobio\"/>\n\nLate in the 1970s, Locke became pregnant by Eastwood twice;<ref name=\"McGilligan\"/> she aborted both pregnancies.<ref name=\"Catholic Sentinel\">{{cite web|url=https://catholicsentinel.org/Content/News/Local/Article/Hollywood-love-affair-with-abortions-topic-of-The-Choices-We-Made-/2/35/7248|title=Hollywood love affair with abortions topic of 'The Choices We Made'|date=April 4, 1991|publisher=Catholic Sentinel}}</ref>{{efn|Locke explained in her autobiography: \"Before I had met Clint my gynecologist had suggested and fitted for me an IUD. Because my sex life was not very active, he did not think I should be constantly taking birth control pills. Clint complained of the IUD{{spaced ndash}}it was uncomfortable for him, he said. And he too was not in favor of birth control pills, so he suggested a special clinic at Cedars Hospital where they taught a 'natural' method of birth control. It was the same 'rhythm' system that historically has been used to determine the fertile days for those who are attempting to achieve pregnancy. Of course, it could be used for the opposite results as well. Not only was I taught their method but I was constantly monitored with regular pregnancy checks. The whole process was awkward and entailed taking my temperature every morning and marking the calendar, etc. It was demanding and ultimately it had failed twice.\"<ref name=\"autobio\"/>}} \"I'd feel sorry for any child that had me for a mother,\" she previously told columnist [[Dick Kleiner]] in 1969.<ref>''The Times and Democrat''. Orangeburg, South Carolina. July 29, 1969. p. 9</ref> After her second abortion, Locke underwent a [[tubal ligation]] at [[UCLA Medical Center]] in mid-1979, citing Eastwood's admancy that parenthood would not fit into their lifestyle.<ref name=\"autobio\"/> When this became public knowledge a decade after the fact, Eastwood issued a statement:\n\n{{bquote|I adamantly deny and deeply resent the accusation that either one of those abortions or the tubal ligation were done at my demand, request or even suggestion. As to the abortions, I told Locke that whether to have children or terminate her pregnancies was a decision entirely hers. Particularly with regard to the tubal ligation, I encouraged Locke to make her own decision after she had consulted with a physician about the appropriateness of and the necessity for that surgical procedure.<ref name=\"Thompson\"/><ref name=\"Schickel\">{{cite book|author=Richard Schickel|title= Clint Eastwood: A Biography|year=1996|publisher=Random House|isbn=0679749918}}</ref>}}\n\nLocke professed mixed feelings on the matter, stating in one chapter of her autobiography that she was grateful she hadn't had Eastwood's children, while writing in another, \"I couldn't help but think that that baby, with both Clint's and my best qualities, would be extraordinary.\"<ref name=\"autobio\"/> Eastwood claimed Locke told him on multiple occasions that she never wanted to have children.<ref>\"Sandra Locke bitter, shocked about split with Clint Eastwood\". ''Hartford Courant'', May 18, 1989</ref>\n\nEastwood and Locke were still cohabiting when, in the latter half of the 1980s, he secretly fathered another woman's two children<ref>{{cite news |first=Jeremy|last=Fuster|title=Sondra Locke, Oscar-Nominated Actress and Longtime Clint Eastwood Partner, Dies at 74|date= December 13, 2018|website=[[TheWrap]]|url=https://www.thewrap.com/sondra-locke-oscar-nominated-actress-dies-74/}}</ref><ref name=\"Leonard\">[https://www.pressreader.com/uk/daily-mail/20190201/282200832154202 Dirty Harry's Dirty Secret] by Tom Leonard, ''Daily Mail'', 31 January 2019.</ref> \u2013 a fact that did not come to light for almost two decades.{{efn|Although the existence of Eastwood's offspring by Jacelyn Reeves was reported in tabloids such as ''[[Star (magazine)|Star]]''<ref>{{cite news|title=Clint Eastwood's Secret 4-Year Love Comes Out of Hiding|first=Stephen|last=Viens|date= February 27, 1990|work=[[Star (magazine)|Star]]}}</ref> and in Locke's autobiography during the 1990s, it continued to be ignored by reputable media sources until about 2006.<ref>The Reeves children are not included in the count, for instance, at {{cite news|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20143212,00.html|title=Passages|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|first=Jeremy|last=Helligar|date=January 13, 1997|quote=News anchor Dina Ruiz, 31, more than made husband Clint Eastwood's day when she gave birth to the couple's first child, an 8-lb. 4-oz. girl named Morgan, on Dec. 12 in Los Angeles. This is the 66-year-old actor-director's fifth child....}}</ref> As late as 2003, for instance, [[A&E (TV channel)|A&E]] produced a two-hour, authorized ''[[Biography (TV program)|Biography]]'' episode on Eastwood which gave the false impression he had a mere total of four children,<ref>\"Behind the Scenes with Clint\". ''Dallas Morning News''. October 4, 2003.</ref> when he in fact has at least eight.<ref name=\"Bergen\"/><ref name=\"Leonard\"/>}} Despite her affirmed ignorance, Locke sensed growing tension in the relationship around 1985, recollecting that \"Although I definitely still loved Clint, I didn't very much ''like'' him.\"<ref name=\"autobio\"/> In retrospect, she gathered \"either he changed from white to black, or I had been living with somebody I didn't even know.\"<ref name=\"doco\"/>\n\n====Palimony suit====\n\nAccording to court testimony, Locke confronted Eastwood over his [[passive-aggressive behavior]] on December 29, 1988,{{efn|Eastwood's passive-aggressive gestures toward Locke included inviting Jane Brolin \u2013 a woman he was having an affair with \u2013 to join Locke and himself on their annual ski trip to Sun Valley. The two women got into a row just before New Year's Eve, Locke recalling, \"I wanted to hit her, to pull every hair out of her head.\"<ref name=\"autobio\"/>}} eliciting estrangement between the couple.<ref name=\"Furtado 8-31-13\"/><ref name=\"Parish\"/> Locke testified that after she and Eastwood made their final public appearance at the American Cinema Awards on January 6, they spent exactly two nights together,<ref name=\"People 5-15-89\"/> without intimate contact.<ref name=\"McGilligan\"/> Eastwood then effectively vacated their Bel-Air mansion, sleeping in the adjacent gardener's quarters or at his apartment in [[Burbank]].<ref name=\"McGilligan\"/> Locke thought Eastwood was acting weird \"because he wasn't number one at the box-office anymore, or because he was facing his mortality.\"<ref name=\"McGilligan\"/> (Eastwood was 58 at the time.) As far as she was concerned their relationship was still salvageable.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://50plusworld.com/celebrating-seniors-clint-eastwood-turns-85-politics-and-passion-4-of-5/|title=Celebrating Seniors - Clint Eastwood Turns 85 - Politics and Passion|first=Anita|last=Hamilton}} June 3, 2015.</ref>\n\n[[File:Eastwood Bird Cannes.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Michael Zelniker, Clint Eastwood, Sondra Locke and Forest Whitaker promoting the film \"Bird\" at the Cannes film festival.|[[Michael Zelniker]], [[Clint Eastwood]], Sondra Locke and [[Forest Whitaker]] promoting ''[[Bird (1988 film)|Bird]]'' (1988) at the [[1988 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes film festival]].]]\n\nOn the morning of April 3<ref name=\"Schickel\"/> or 4,<ref name=\"McGilligan\"/> Eastwood complained in the kitchen that Locke was \"sitting on my only real estate in Los Angeles\" and bolted.<ref name=\"autobio\"/> Locke later defensively declared: \"Clint is not good at direct communication. He really is a man of few words. You might just as well have a direct confrontation with a wall.\"<ref name=\"Hall\">{{cite news|url=https://www.questia.com/article/1G1-61171112/clint-v-sondra-for-a-fistful-of-dollars-magnum-farce|title=Clint v Sondra for a Fistful of Dollars|first=Allan|last=Hall}} September 12, 1996.</ref> On April 10, 1989, Eastwood or someone working for him changed the locks on the family residence, moved Locke's possessions into storage, and posted security guards at the front gate.<ref name=\"McGilligan\"/> Locke was shooting ''Impulse'' (1990) at the time of the lockout;<ref name=\"Furtado 10-19-13\"/> she filed a [[palimony]] suit on April 26.<ref name=\"Puig\"/>\n\nDuring their 14 years as man and wife [[de facto]], Locke and Eastwood acquired four homes, including a spacious retreat in [[Sun Valley, Idaho]] and the [[Rising River Ranch]] in [[Burney, California|Burney]].<ref name=\"McGilligan\"/> Locke sought equal division of property, requesting title to the house in Bel-Air and to the West Hollywood place Eastwood had been leasing to Gordon Anderson since 1982.<ref name=\"Parish\"/> She also asked Judge Dana Senit Henry to bar Eastwood from the Bel-Air house \"because I know him to have a terrible temper ... and he has frequently been abusive to me.\"<ref>\"Eastwood's Ex Hit Hard by Sudden Impact of Breakup\". ''St. Louis Post-Dispatch'', May 24, 1989.</ref> (At 6'4\" Eastwood stood a full foot taller than her.<ref>\"Locke Is Big With Eastwood\". Vernon Scott, ''Lebanon Daily News'', December 20, 1977</ref>)\n\nLocke battled Eastwood for 20 months; she developed [[breast cancer]] during the proceedings and said the treatments sapped her will to fight.<ref name=\"Young\"/>{{efn|Scientific research studies have not found a cause-and-effect relationship between abortion and breast cancer.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cancer.org/cancer/cancer-causes/medical-treatments/abortion-and-breast-cancer-risk.html|title=Abortion and Breast Cancer Risk|publisher= [[American Cancer Society]]}}</ref>}} In November 1990, the parties reached a private settlement wherein Eastwood set up a $1.5 million, multi-year film development/directing pact for Locke at [[Warner Bros.]] in exchange for dropping the suit.<ref name=\"E! 9-11-96\"/> She got the West Hollywood property, about $500,000 cash and unspecified monthly support payments as well.<ref name=\"Schickel\"/> Eastwood kept their pet parrot Putty and renamed him Paco.<ref name=\"McGilligan\"/>\n\n====Fraud suit====\n\nIn June 1995, Locke sued Eastwood again, for [[fraud]] and [[breach of fiduciary duty]], alleging the deal with WB was a sham.<ref>\"Eastwood is target of another Locke Lawsuit\". ''Chicago Tribune'', June 7, 1995</ref><ref>\"Locke Says She Was 'Humiliated'\". ''Los Angeles Times'', September 13, 1996</ref> The studio had rejected the 30 or more projects she proposed and never used her as a director.<ref>\"Sondra Locke continues to battle ex-beau Clint Eastwood\". Josh Young, ''Santa Cruz Sentinel'', March 26, 1995</ref><ref>\"Locke cries foul at producing deal\". Liz Smith, ''The Palm Beach Post'', April 30, 1994</ref> According to Locke's attorney Peggy Garrity, Eastwood committed \"the ultimate betrayal\" by arranging the \"bogus\" deal as a way to keep her out of work.<ref name=\"Daily News 9-25-96\">{{cite web |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1696&dat=19960923&id=gQsbAAAAIBAJ&pg=4859,2700108|title=Eastwood, ex-lover settle court battle as jurors deliberate|work=Daily News|date=September 25, 1996}}</ref> Garrity added that Eastwood had held out the allegedly bogus deal \"like a dangled carrot\" to persuade Locke to drop the earlier palimony suit.<ref name=\"Daily News 9-25-96\"/>\n\nThe case went to trial in September 1996.<ref>{{cite news |last=O'Neill |first=Ann W.|title=Sondra Locke Suing Clint Eastwood |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/doc/293385865.html|date=September 18, 1996|accessdate=April 29, 2010}}</ref> One juror disclosed that the panel sided with Locke by a 10-to-2 vote (nine votes are needed for a verdict) and were only debating the amount.<ref name=\"E! 9-24-96\">Errico, Marcus (September 24, 1996). [http://www.eonline.com/news/33601/clint-eastwood-pays-off-sondra-locke \"Clint Eastwood Pays Off Sondra Locke\"]. ''E! News''.</ref> Before any court decision could be made, Locke settled the case with Eastwood for an undisclosed amount of money.<ref name=\"E! 9-24-96\"/> The outcome, Locke said, sent a \"loud and clear\" message to Hollywood, \"that people cannot get away with whatever they want to just because they're powerful.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Eastwood Settles with Sondra Locke |work=[[Philadelphia Inquirer]] |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=PI&p_action=search&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EB32DC62E746ACD |date=September 25, 1996|accessdate=April 10, 2013}}</ref> According to Locke, \"In this business, people get so accustomed to being abused, they just accept the abuse and say, 'Well, that's just the way it is.' Well, it isn't.\"<ref name=\"Parish\"/>\n\nFor his part, Eastwood waved the lawsuit off as a \"dime-novel plot,\"<ref name=\"E! 9-24-96\"/> continuing, \u201cIt's all about money ... about getting something for nothing.\"<ref>''Los Angeles Times'', 9.25.96</ref> He accused Locke of using her cancer to gain the jury's sympathy: \"She plays the victim very well. Unfortunately she had cancer and so she plays that card.\"<ref>\"Clint Eastwood - Interview - Western Movie Star\". [[Bernard Weinraub]], ''[[Playboy]]'', March 1997</ref>\n\nLocke brought a separate action against Warner Bros. for allegedly conspiring with Eastwood to sabotage her directorial career.<ref>O'Neill, Ann W. (May 23, 1999). [http://articles.latimes.com/1999/may/23/local/me-40206 \"Settlement Could Make Locke's Day\"]. ''Los Angeles Times''.</ref> As had happened with the previous lawsuit, this ended in an out-of-court settlement, in May 1999.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eonline.com/news/38212/vindication-for-clint-eastwood-s-ex-lover|title=Vindication for Clint Eastwood's Ex-Lover|work=[[E! News]]|first=Joal|last=Ryan|date=May 25, 1999}}</ref> By then, Locke had fired Garrity and hired [[Neil Papiano]] to represent her.<ref name=\"LA Times 6-6-99\">[http://articles.latimes.com/1999/jun/06/local/me-44776 This Time, Judge Judy's a Defendant] Ann W. O'Neill, ''Los Angeles Times'', June 6, 1999</ref>{{efn|In June 1999, Garrity sued Locke to get paid for persuading the appellate court to reinstate ''Locke v. Warner Bros. Inc''.<ref name=\"LA Times 6-6-99\"/> WB had requested [[summary judgement]] after the original March 1994 filing, which the court granted, but in August 1997 the decision was reversed.<ref name=\"Eliot\"/> Garrity put 2,500 hours of work into the case, only to be dumped by Locke and replaced by Papiano in May 1998.<ref name=\"LA Times 6-6-99\"/> Garrity won her lawsuit, and remarked that the payment would not have cost Locke a dime more than what was already going to legal fees, since it would simply have come out of Papiano's one-third contingency fee.<ref name=\"Garrity\">{{cite book|author=Peggy Garrity|title=In the Game: The Highs and Lows of a Trailblazing Trial Lawyer|year=2016|publisher=She Writes Press|isbn=978-1631521065}}</ref>}} The agreement with Warner Bros., Locke said, was \"a happy ending.\"<ref>[http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20128608,00.html The Battle's Over for Eastwood's Ex ]. ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'', July 5, 1999</ref> \"I feel elated. This has been the best day in a long, long time,\" Locke said outside the courthouse.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thefreelibrary.com/EASTWOOD'S+EX+SETTLES+WITH+WARNER+BROS-a083612488 |author=Huffaker, Donna |title=Eastwood's ex settles with Warner Bros. |work=[[Los Angeles Daily News]]}}</ref> The case is used in some modern law-school contract textbooks to illustrate the legal concept of [[good faith]].<ref>{{cite book|editor1-first=Nathan|editor1-last=Crystal|editor2-first=Charles|editor2-last=Knapp|editor3-first=Harry|editor3-last=Prince|title=Problems in Contract Law: Cases and Materials|edition=6th|publisher=Aspen Publishing|location=New York City|date=2007|isbn=978-0735598225|pages=470\u201380}}</ref>\n\n===Illness; last relationship===\n\nA lifelong non-smoker (save for a few film roles), Locke practiced [[Transcendental Meditation]]<ref>\"Sondra Locke: A match for the macho Clint Eastwood\". Bart Mills, ''Chicago Tribune'', June 25, 1978</ref> and worked out with weights, though she hated running.<ref>\"Sondra Locke and her career as sidekick\". Chris Chase, ''The New York Times'', December 23, 1983</ref> In September 1990, she confirmed reports that she had breast cancer.<ref name=\"Philadelphia Enquirer 9/20/90\">\"Sick-bay report\". ''The Philadelphia Enquirer'', September 20, 1990</ref> \"Due to factors in my personal life, I have sustained two years of extreme and unnecessary stress, which my doctors tell me has been my enemy,\" Locke said at the time.<ref name=\"Philadelphia Enquirer 9/20/90\"/> She added that Eastwood never reached out to her after her diagnosis.<ref name=\"Hall\"/> \"He doesn't care if I live or die.\"<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/Sondra-Locke-Clipping-Magazine-photo/dp/B00CBLD9FY Sondra Locke Clipping Magazine photo orig 1pg 8x10 M7797 at Amazon's Entertainment Collectibles Store<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nLocke underwent a double [[mastectomy]] at [[Cedars-Sinai Medical Center]], followed by [[chemotherapy]].<ref name=\"Thompson\"/> During treatment, she began dating an intern assigned to perform the post-surgical checkup, Scott Cunneen (born September 10, 1961 in [[Long Beach, California]]).<ref name=\"nndb\"/><ref name=\"Waxman\"/><ref name=\"Eliot\"/><ref>{{cite journal |date=June 1991|title=Swingers and Roundabouts|journal=[[Film Review (magazine)|Film Review]] |publisher=Orpheus Pub. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ap0qAQAAIAAJ}}</ref><ref>[http://www.annonline.com/interviews/971111/biography.html \"Locke Biography\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707145247/http://www.annonline.com/interviews/971111/biography.html |date=July 7, 2011}}. annoline.com. Retrieved October 7, 2012.</ref> Unfazed by their 17-year age difference \u2013 and the fact that Locke was only three years younger than his mother<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.californiabirthindex.org/birth/mary_ann_forman_born_1941_2335322|title=Mary Ann Forman, Born 01/19/1941 in California |website=www.californiabirthindex.org}}</ref> \u2013 they soon went public with the romance, dining at paparazzi hotspot [[Spago]] on one of their early dates in November 1990.<ref>[https://www.gettyimages.com/detail/news-photo/actress-sondra-locke-and-boyfriend-scott-cunneen-on-news-photo/156132068 Actress Sondra Locke and boyfriend Scott Cunneen on November 10, 1990... News Photo] ''GettyImages''</ref> Cunneen moved in with her in the spring of 1991.<ref name=\"autobio\"/> She called it a \"real, supportive, and equal relationship.\"<ref name=\"autobio\"/>\n\nIn February 2001, Locke purchased a six-bedroom home in the [[Hollywood Hills]], where she resided for the remainder of her life.<ref>[http://virtualglobetrotting.com/map/sondra-lockes-house/ \"Sondra Locke's House\"]. virtualglobetrotting.com. February 25, 2009. Retrieved October 7, 2012.</ref> She and Cunneen eventually broke up, albeit without publicity, since she had faded from public view.<ref name=\"Eliot\"/>\n\nIn 2015, after a 25-year period of apparent remission,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2018/12/oscar-nominee-sondra-locke-has-died.html|title=Sondra Locke, Girlfriend Turned Enemy of Clint Eastwood, Is Dead|first=Bethy|last=Squires|date=December 13, 2018|publisher=Vulture}}</ref> Locke's cancer returned and [[metastasis|metastacized]] to her bones.<ref name=\"The Blast\">{{cite web|url=https://theblast.com/clint-eastwood-sondra-locke-death-certificate-cardiac-arrest|title=Clint Eastwood's Longtime GF, Sondra Locke Died from Cardiac Arrest|first1=Gary|last1=Trock|first2=Liz|last2=Walters|date= December 15, 2018|work=The Blast}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nLocke died on November 3, 2018 at the age of 74 from a [[cardiac arrest]] related to breast and bone cancers.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://radaronline.com/exclusives/2018/12/sondra-locke-dead-clint-eastwood/|title=Clint Eastwood's Longtime Partner Sondra Locke Dead At 74|last=Jacob|first=Mary|date=December 13, 2018|website=RadorOnline|publisher=American Media, Inc.|access-date=December 13, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/sondra-locke-dead-dies-heart-is-a-lonely-hunter-1203089402|title=Oscar Nominee Sondra Locke Dies at 74|last=McNary|first=Dave|date=December 14, 2018|website=Variety|access-date=December 14, 2018}}</ref> Her remains were [[cremated]] on November 9, at [[Pierce Brothers Westwood Village Memorial Park and Mortuary]] and the ashes were given to her widower, Gordon Anderson.<ref name=\"The Blast\"/>\n\nLocke's death was not publicized until December 14 \u2013 the day her ex's latest blockbuster ''[[The Mule (2018 film)|The Mule]]'' (2018) opened in theaters nationwide. The [[Associated Press]] said \"It is not clear why it took nearly six weeks to come to light.\"<ref name=\"Dalton\"/> According to the AP report, attempts to reach Anderson for comment were unsuccessful.<ref name=\"Dalton\"/> Locke left Anderson an estimated fortune of $20 million,<ref name=\"Hammond\"/> and seemed to have always supported him financially.<ref name=\"Kennedy\"/><ref>\"[https://www.questia.com/article/1G1-111319455/in-hollywood-there-s-talk-of-little-else-when-sondra In Hollywood, There's Talk of Little Else. When Sondra Locke Sued Clint Eastwood for Sabotaging Her Career, It Looked like the Sour Revenge of a Jilted Lover. but One Month and a $5Million Pay-Off Later, She Has Emerged as the Good, He as the Bad, and Tinseltown as Just Plain Ugly]. Julia Phillips, ''The Mail on Sunday'', October 27, 1996</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n\nLocke is remembered as an early pioneer for women in Hollywood.<ref name=\"Welk\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/sondra-locke-remembered-as-early-pioneer-women-hollywood/|title=Sondra Locke Remembered as \u2018Early Pioneer\u2019 for Women in Hollywood|first=Brian|last=Welk|date=December 14, 2018|publisher=[[TheWrap]]}}</ref> She was one of 11 female filmmakers in 1990, the year WB released her sophomore feature, ''Impulse''.<ref name=\"LA Times 9-29-96\">\"Locke Feels Vindicated After Lawsuit\". Ann W. O'Neill, ''Los Angeles Times'', September 29, 1996</ref> By the time of ''Trading Favors'' (1997), her fourth effort, still only eight percent of all films were made by women, per the [[Directors Guild of America]].<ref name=\"LA Times 9-29-96\"/>\n\nLocke's influence as a feminist icon was duly acknowledged by the mainstream press. In 1989, Claudia Puig of the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' described her lawsuit against Clint Eastwood as a \"precedent-setting legal case, as it raises the question of whether a woman, who is legally married to one man, can claim palimony rights from another.\"<ref name=\"Puig\"/> [[Voluntary childlessness|Childfree]] by choice \u2013 unusual for a person of her generation<ref>[https://www.economist.com/international/2017/07/27/the-rise-of-childlessness The rise of childlessness] ''The Economist'', July 27, 2017</ref> \u2013 Locke was among the first celebrities to publicly discuss her abortion experiences.<ref name=\"Catholic Sentinel\"/> The disclosure made Locke \"a talking-point in America's sexual politics debate,\" according to ''[[The Guardian]]'''s [[Peter Bradshaw]].<ref name=\"Bradshaw\"/> Locke's subsequent relationship with a doctor young enough to be her son added to her notoriety.<ref>\"Just Call Me Dirty Harriet\". Glenys Roberts, ''London Daily Mail'', December 27, 1997</ref>\n\n[[File:Locke HS Yearbook 2.jpg|thumb|Locke in 1961]]\n\nDuring the last third of her life, Locke maintained she was [[blacklisted]] from the film industry as a result of her acrimonious split from Eastwood.<ref name=\"podcast1\"/> His career moved forward unscathed.<ref name=\"Parish\"/> Peggy Garrity, Locke's former counsel, recalled the courtroom drama in her 2016 book ''In the Game: The Highs and Lows of a Trailblazing Trial Lawyer''. Garrity revealed that Locke's 1999 confidential settlement from WB \"was for many millions more than the settlement with Clint had been.\"<ref name=\"Garrity\"/> ''Locke v. Warner Bros. Inc'' also catalyzed changes within the legal system. In a landmark decision,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.questia.com/magazine/1G1-55534573/go-ahead-make-my-day-locke-vs-eastwood-case-leads|title=Go Ahead, Make My Day : Locke vs. Eastwood Case Leads to Landmark Decision |first=Mark|last=Fitzgerald}} ''[[Editor & Publisher]]'', July 31, 1999.</ref> California's [[Supreme Court of California|Supreme Court]] ruled that access to civil trials could no longer be closed off to the public.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rcfp.org/public-media-have-right-attend-civil-trials/|title=Public, media have right to attend civil trials|date=August 9, 1999|publisher=Reporters Committee for Freedom of the Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1999-may-07-mn-34779-story.html|title=Court Leaning Toward Access to Civil Trials|first=Maura|last=Dolan}} ''Los Angeles Times'', May 7, 1999.</ref>\n\nOther actresses admire Locke as someone who merited respect on the strength of her directorial accomplishments, however short-lived. [[Frances Fisher]], who dated and had a child by Eastwood in the 1990s, applauded her predecessor for \"her courageous battle with the cancerous patriarchal power structure in our industry.\"<ref>[https://www.instagram.com/p/BrYQK8vB7PM/ francesfisher on Instagram: \u201c#RestInParadise dear friend #SondraLocke] 12.14.18</ref> Rosanna Arquette commented that Locke \"had laser vision\" and \"was great with actors,\" adding, \"It is horrible to be blackballed.\"<ref>[https://twitter.com/RoArquette/status/1073465228308885504 Rosanna Arquette\ud83c\udf0e\u270c\ud83c\udffc on Twitter: \"I worked with Sondra Locke as a director in 1996. She was thoughtful and kind ..had laser vision she was great with actors. It is horrible to be black balled.\" / Twitter] 12.13.18</ref>\n\nNumerous outlets faced backlash over their chosen headlines for Locke's obituary. In what was deemed a [[sexist]] epitaph,<ref name=\"Welk\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.themarysue.com/in-memory-of-sondra-locke-obituary/|title=In Memory of Sondra Locke, Not Her Relationship|first=Kate|last=Gardner|date=December 14, 2018|publisher=The Mary Sue}}</ref> virtually every major publication prefaced news of her death by tagging Eastwood's name atop the article. Fans on social media were quick to point out that Locke was an Oscar nominee before she even met him. Women's blog ''[[Jezebel (website)|Jezebel]]'' criticized ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' for ostensibly depicting Locke as a nonentity;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://jezebel.com/this-is-how-a-woman-gets-written-out-of-her-own-obituar-1831097072|title=This Is How a Woman Gets Written Out of Her Own Obituary|first=Hazel|last=Cills|date=December 14, 2018|publisher=[[Jezebel (website)|Jezebel]]}}</ref> ''THR'' subsequently changed its headline.<ref name=\"Welk\"/> News organization ''[[TheWrap]]'' \u2013 whose editor, [[Sharon Waxman]], reviewed Locke's memoir for ''[[The Washington Post]]'' in 1997 \u2013 opined that her story \"should stir resonance in this age of the [[#MeToo movement]].\"<ref name=\"Welk\"/> In a tribute to the late actress, author [[Sarah Weinman]] wrote, \"Sondra Locke, like [[Barbara Loden]], deserves to be known for her work, not for the famous man she was disastrously involved with.\"<ref name=\"Welk\"/>\n\nIn 1971, fifth-graders at Eastside Elementary in Locke's hometown of Shelbyville, Tennessee were left star-struck when Locke made a visit and held pretend \"auditions\" in the class to show them what it was like in Hollywood.<ref name=\"DeGennaro\"/> One student, [[Cameron Watson (actor)|Cameron Watson]], was influenced by Locke and is now an actor/director. Watson's period drama ''[[Our Very Own (2005 film)|Our Very Own]]'' (2005) takes place in Shelbyville in 1978 and focuses on a group of teenagers who want to meet Locke when she returns to town for the local premiere of ''[[Every Which Way but Loose]]''. Watson decided to do the movie after performing a standup routine about Locke and about how people in Shelbyville were obsessed with her.<ref>''The Tennessean'', 4.27.04</ref> Locke attended one of those performances at the [[Tiffany Theater]] in West Hollywood. \"The minute she heard the first reference to her or to her family, she threw up her arms: 'What the hell is this?'\" Watson said. \"By the end of the reading, she was doubled over.\"<ref>''The Jackson Sun'', 6.27.04</ref> Locke gave the script her blessing and accepted an invitation to be special guest at the film's premiere.<ref>''The Tennessean from Nashville'', 8.7.05</ref> The movie was a \u201cspecial gift\u201d to Locke, according to Deborah Obenchain, another Eastside student who said she didn\u2019t think Locke really understood her impact on the small town she once called home. \u201cI think it meant just as much to her. \u2026 In our own way \u2026 we got to live out a little bit of our dreams by making the movie and meeting her.\u201d<ref name=\"DeGennaro\"/>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===As actress===\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n! class=\"unsortable\"| {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| 1968\n| ''[[The Heart Is a Lonely Hunter (film)|The Heart Is a Lonely Hunter]]''\n| Margaret 'Mick' Kelly\n| Nominated\u2014[[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress]]<br>Nominated\u2014[[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Motion Picture]]<br>Nominated\u2014[[Golden Globe Award for New Star of the Year \u2013 Actress|Golden Globe Award for Most Promising Newcomer \u2014 Female]]<br>Nominated\u2014[[Laurel Awards|Laurel Award for Female Supporting Performance]]<br>Nominated\u2014[[Laurel Awards|Laurel Award for Female New Face]]\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.avclub.com/r-i-p-sondra-locke-oscar-nominated-star-of-the-heart-1831088914|title=The Heart Is A Lonely Hunter - Sondra Locke and Alan Arkin|website=MSN|accessdate=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1970\n| ''[[Cover Me Babe]]''\n| Melisse\n|\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.shockcinemamagazine.com/cover.html|title=Cover Me Babe|website=www.shockcinemamagazine.com|accessdate=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1971\n| ''[[Willard (1971 film)|Willard]]''\n| Joan\n|\n| <ref name=\"horrorsociety.com\">{{cite web |url=https://www.horrorsociety.com/2018/12/14/rip-willard-actress-sondra-locke/|title=RIP Willard Actress Sondra Locke|date=December 14, 2018|website=Horror Society|accessdate=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1972\n| ''[[A Reflection of Fear]]''\n| Marguerite\n|\n| <ref name=\"horrorsociety.com\"/>\n|-\n| 1972\n| ''[[Night Gallery]]''\n| Sheila Gray\n| Episode: \"A Feast of Blood\"\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/night-gallery/episode-602178/203447|title=Night Gallery - TV Guide|website=TVGuide.com|accessdate=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1972\n| ''[[The F.B.I. (TV series)|The F.B.I.]]''\n| Regina Mason\n| Episode: \"Dark Christmas\"\n| <ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|-\n| 1973\n| ''[[Cannon (TV series)|Cannon]]''\n| Trish\n| Episode: \"Death of a Stone Seahorse\"\n| <ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|-\n| 1973\n| ''[[The ABC Afternoon Playbreak]]''\n| Nora Sells\n| Episode: \"My Secret Mother\"\n| <ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|-\n| 1973\n| ''The Gondola''\n| Jackie\n| TV movie\n| <ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|-\n| 1974\n| ''[[The Second Coming of Suzanne]]''\n| Suzanne\n|\n| <ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|-\n| 1974\n| ''[[Kung Fu (TV series)|Kung Fu]]''\n| Gwyneth Jenkins\n| Episode: \"This Valley of Terror\"\n| <ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|-\n| 1974\n| ''[[Planet of the Apes (TV series)|Planet of the Apes]]''\n| Amy\n| Episode: \"The Cure\"\n| <ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|-\n| 1975\n| ''[[Barnaby Jones]]''\n| Alicia\n| Episode: \"The Orchid Killer\"\n| <ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|-\n| 1975\n| ''Cannon''\n| Stacey Murdock\n| Episode: \"A Touch of Venom\"\n| <ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|-\n| 1976\n| ''[[Joe Forrester]]''\n| N/A\n| Episode: \"A Game of Love\"\n| <ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|-\n| 1976\n| ''[[The Outlaw Josey Wales]]''\n| Laura Lee\n|\n| <ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|-\n| 1977\n| ''[[Death Game]]''\n| Agatha Jackson\n|\n| <ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|-\n| 1977\n| ''[[The Shadow of Chikara]]''\n| Drusilla Wilcox\n|\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.moriareviews.com/horror/shadow-of-chikara-1977.htm|title=Shadow of Chikara (1977)|date=March 9, 2010|publisher=|accessdate=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1977\n| ''[[The Gauntlet (film)|The Gauntlet]]''\n| Augustina 'Gus' Mally\n|\n| <ref name=\"Bradshaw\"/>\n|-\n| 1978\n| ''[[Every Which Way but Loose (film)|Every Which Way but Loose]]''\n| Lynn Halsey-Taylor\n|\n| <ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/obituaries/2018/12/14/sondra-locke-actress-appeared-clint-eastwood-hit-films-1970s/ Sandra Locke appeared with Clint Eastwood in hit films] Telegraph Retrieved December 18, 2018</ref>\n|-\n| 1979\n| ''Friendships, Secrets and Lies''\n| Jessie Dunne\n| TV movie\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1979/12/03/archives/tv-friendships-secrets-and-lies.html|title=TV: 'Friendships, Secrets and Lies'|first=John J.|last=O'Connor|date=December 3, 1979|publisher=|accessdate=December 18, 2018|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1980\n| ''[[Bronco Billy]]''\n| Antoinette Lily\n|Nominated\u2014[[Razzie Award for Worst Actress]]\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.svenskfilmdatabas.se/sv/item/?type=film&itemid=7745|title=Bronco Billy (1980) \u2013 Svensk Filmdatabas|publisher=|access