y|date=March 22, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===As director===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! class=\"unsortable\"| {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[Ratboy]]''\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://thewandrinstar.wordpress.com/2013/11/20/sondra-lockes-ratboy-a-modern-day-fairy-tale-en/|title=Sondra Locke's Ratboy: A modern day fairy tale|first=David|last=Furtado|date=November 20, 2013|publisher=|accessdate=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1990\n| ''[[Impulse (1990 film)|Impulse]]''\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2018/dec/14/sondra-locke-obituary|title=Sondra Locke obituary|first=Ryan|last=Gilbey|date=December 14, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=December 17, 2018|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1995\n| ''Death in Small Doses''\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://letterboxd.com/film/death-in-small-doses-1995/|title=Death in Small Doses (1995)|publisher=|accessdate=December 18, 2018|via=letterboxd.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[Trading Favors]]''\n| <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/actress-director-sondra-locke-clint-021743085.html|title=Actress and Director Sondra Locke, Clint Eastwood's Former Girlfriend of 14 Years, Dies at 74|website=www.yahoo.com|accessdate=December 18, 2018}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Stage==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Show\n! Role\n! Location\n! {{Tooltip|Ref(s)|Reference(s)}}\n|-\n| 1962\n| ''[[Life with Father]]''\n| Mary Wickes\n| Tucker Theater, Murfreesboro, Tennessee\n|<ref name=\"DNJ 11-2-62\"/>\n|-\n| 1963\n| ''[[The Crucible]]''\n| Mary Warren\n| Tucker Theater, Murfreesboro, Tennessee\n|<ref name=\"DNJ 2-24-63\"/>\n|-\n| 1964\n| ''Life with Mother''\n| N/A\n| Belcourt Playhouse, Nashville, Tennessee\n|<ref>{{cite news|title=Several Days With the Days|newspaper=[[The Nashville Tennessean]]|date=February 16, 1964|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/111970652}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1964\n| ''[[The Innocents (play)|The Innocents]]''\n| Flora\n| Circle Theater, Nashville Tennessee\n|<ref>{{cite news|title=Shivers Missing in 'The Innocents'|newspaper=[[The Nashville Tennessean]]|date=June 18, 1964|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/111607043}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1964\n| ''A Thousand Clowns''\n| Dr. Sandra Markowitz\n| Circle Theater, Nashville, Tennessee\n|<ref>{{cite news|title=Erwin Has Rare Aplomb; Poise Brings Applause|newspaper=[[The Nashville Tennessean]]|date=August 20, 1964|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/112073032}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1965\n| ''[[Night of the Iguana]]''\n| Charlotte Goodall\n| Circle Theater, Nashville, Tennessee\n|<ref name=\"Tennessean 9-19-65\"/>\n|-\n| 1965\n| ''[[Oh Dad, Poor Dad, Mamma's Hung You in the Closet and I'm Feelin' So Sad]]''\n| Rosalie\n| Circle Theater, Nashville, Tennessee\n|<ref>{{cite news|title=Theater To Hold Tryouts|newspaper=[[The Nashville Tennessean]]|date=October 17, 1965|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/112090155}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1965\n| ''[[The Glass Menagerie]]''\n| Laura Wingfield\n| Circle Theater, Nashville, Tennessee\n|<ref>{{cite news|title='Menagerie' Opens|newspaper=[[The Nashville Tennessean]]|date=November 21, 1965|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/111833460}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1967\n| ''[[Tiger at the Gates]]''\n| Helen of Troy\n| Vanderbilt Theatre, Nashville, Tennessee\n|<ref>{{cite news|title='Tiger at the Gates' At Vanderbuilt Theater|newspaper=[[The Nashville Tennessean]]|date=January 20, 1967|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/113221744}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{notelist|60em}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Film|Television}}\n*[[List of American film actresses]]\n*[[List of female film and television directors]]\n*[[List of Middle Tennessee State University people]]\n*[[List of people from Los Angeles]]\n*[[List of people from Tennessee]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name}}\n*{{TCMDb name}}\n*{{Worldcat id|lccn-n93-89860}}\n\n{{Clint Eastwood|state=collapsed}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Locke, Sondra}}\n[[Category:Actresses from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:American autobiographers]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American women film directors]]\n[[Category:American women non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Burials at Westwood Village Memorial Park Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Deaths from bone cancer]]\n[[Category:Deaths from breast cancer]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in California]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Middle Tennessee State University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Madison County, Alabama]]\n[[Category:People from Shelbyville, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Women autobiographers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Writers from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:20th-century American biographers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American biographers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n", "name_user": "Alaynia", "label": "safe", "comment": "in Dalliances heading, changed a word.. nothing to noting because prior editor had used the wrong word.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sondra_Locke"}
{"title_page": "Long Vacation", "text_new": "{{no footnotes|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Long Vacation \n| native_name          = {{Infobox name module|kanji=\u30ed\u30f3\u30b0\u30d0\u30b1\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3}}\n| image                = Long vacation.png\n| caption              = Long Vacation title card\n| genre                = Drama, romance\n| camera               = \n| picture_format       = \n| audio_format         = \n| runtime              = \n| creator              = \n| writer               = [[Eriko Kitagawa]]\n| director             = K\u014dz\u014d Nagayama<br/>[[Masayuki Suzuki (director)|Masayuki Suzuki]]<br/>Hirotsugu Usui\n| developer            = \n| producer             = \n| executive_producer   = \n| starring             = [[Takuya Kimura]]<br/>[[Tomoko Yamaguchi]]\n| voices               =\n| narrated             = \n| theme_music_composer = \n| opentheme            = ''[[La La La Love Song]]'' ([[Toshinobu Kubota]]) with [[Naomi Campbell]]\n| composer             = \n| endtheme             =\n| country              = Japan\n| location             = \n| language             = Japanese\n| network              = [[Fuji TV]]\n| first_aired          = 15 April 1996\n| last_aired           = 24 June 1996\n| num_series           = 1\n| num_episodes         = 11\n| list_episodes        = \n| preceded_by          = \n| followed_by          = \n| related              = \n| website              = \n}}\n\n'''''Long Vacation''''' ({{lang|ja|\u30ed\u30f3\u30b0\u30d0\u30b1\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3}}, also known as {{lang|ja|\u30ed\u30f3\u30d0\u30b1}}) is a [[Japanese television drama]] series from [[Fuji Television]], first shown in Japan from 15 April to 24 June 1996. [[Takuya Kimura]] and [[Tomoko Yamaguchi]] played the lead characters. The series enjoyed high ratings and was the earliest of a series of hit productions starring Kimura. It features music by [[Cagnet (band)|Cagnet]]. The theme song was ''[[La La La Love Song]]'' by [[Toshinobu Kubota]] with [[Naomi Campbell]].\n\n==Summary==\n\nMinami and Sena meet when Sena's apartment-mate, Asakura, jilts Minami on their wedding day.  Minami learns from Sena that Asakura has left, whereabouts unknown.  Sena allows Minami to move into the apartment, since she is penniless, having given all her money to Asakura, and cannot pay the rent on her apartment.\n\nThis is the beginning of a romance between Sena and Minami. Minami and Sena confide in and console each other about their relationship problems and their lack of success in life.\n\nMinami meets a professional photographer, Sugisaki, who proposes marriage. Finally Sena has a chance of winning a piano competition and going to Boston, joining the symphony orchestra.\n\nThe characters in the series have something in common\u2014if not jobless, they can do no better than secure a temporary job. This is a portrayal of a time when Japan was plagued by deep recession, when its people suffered profound depression from constant failure to earn a stable income. The series also portrays how relationships are made and broken, and explores how people come to depend on each other for solace.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Takuya Kimura]] as {{nihongo|Sena Hidetoshi|\u702c\u540d\u79c0\u4fca}}\n*[[Tomoko Yamaguchi]] as {{nihongo|Hayama Minami|\u8449\u5c71\u5357}}\n*[[Yutaka Takenouchi]] as {{nihongo|Hayama Shinji|\u8449\u5c71\u771f\u4e8c}}\n*[[Takako Matsu]] as {{nihongo|Okusawa Ryoko|\u5965\u6ca2\u6dbc\u5b50}}\n*[[Izumi Inamori]] as {{nihongo|Koishikawa Momoko|\u5c0f\u77f3\u5ddd\u6843\u5b50}}\n*[[Ry\u014d (actress)|Ry\u014d]] as {{nihongo|Himuro Rumiko|\u6c37\u5ba4\u30eb\u30df\u5b50}}\n*[[Leo Morimoto]] as {{nihongo|Professor Sasaki|\u4f50\u3005\u6728\u6559\u6388}}\n*[[Ry\u014dko Hirosue]] as {{nihongo|Saito Takako|\u6589\u85e4\u8cb4\u5b50}}\n*[[Kosuke Toyohara]] as {{nihongo|Sugisaki Tetsuya|\u6749\u5d0e\u54f2\u4e5f}}\n\n==Characters==\n\n*Hidetoshi Sena (24) \u2013 An ambitious pianist with dreams of the big time. After graduating from music school, he teaches at a children's piano school for a small income. He lives in an apartment with a baby grand piano in the living room. Sena practises for piano competitions throughout the series. Despite his seemingly very adept technical ability and Sasaki's high opinion of Sena's playing, Sena constantly meets with failure. The reason for this becomes clearer as the story unfolds. Momoko calls him \"Ayrton\" because his surname resembles that of former motor-racing world champion [[Ayrton Senna]]. He suffers many harsh remarks from arrogant student Takako, but still helps her in her struggle with life.\n*Minami Hayama (31) \u2013 An independent and uninhibited 30-year-old woman. Once in demand as a fashion model, she now works as a small-time model on increasingly infrequent jobs. She is unlucky in love: Her fianc\u00e9 elopes with a younger woman on their wedding day. Through a series of circumstances, Minami comes to stay in Sena's house. Their deepening relationship is a main thread of the drama.\n*Shinji Hayama \u2013 Minami's younger brother. A loafer and notorious womanizer, he is also a talented pianist who is later revealed to have had a promising piano career. He comes to Tokyo with his girlfriend Rumiko, relying on [[pachinko]] winnings to foot the bill. He later buys a bar and runs it with her.\n*Ryoko Okusawa \u2013 A very talented pianist but shy with a sheltered upbringing. She is a student in the same music school that Sena graduated from and considered a future star. Sena develops a crush on her but she seems indifferent toward him. Shinji briefly seduces her but later leaves her.\n*Momoko Koishikawa \u2013 Minami's junior in the modelling company and a close friend of Minami. Despite her ditzy manner, she sometimes makes insightful observations and offers useful advice.\n*Rumiko Himuro \u2013 Shinji's girlfriend.\n*Professor Sasaki \u2013 Sena's mentor and former professor. He often encourages Sena to enter piano competitions.\n*Takako Saito \u2013 A child prodigy who is taught by Sena for a brief time. Initially, her attitude toward Sena is disrespectful.\n*Tetsuya Sugisaki \u2013 A dashing professional photographer who falls for Minami.\n\n==Ratings==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%;\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" background: #f9f9f9;\n|- align=\"center\"\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Episode\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Date\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Rating (%)\n|-\n| 01\n| 15 April 1996\n| 30.6\n|-\n| 02\n| 22 April 1996\n| 28.3\n|-\n| 03\n| 29 April 1996\n| 29.0\n|-\n| 04\n| 6 May 1996\n| 27.6\n|-\n| 05\n| 13 May 1996\n| 27.9\n|-\n| 06\n| 20 May 1996\n| 25.5\n|-\n| 07\n| 27 May 1996\n| 27.7\n|-\n| 08\n| 3 June 1996\n| 29.9\n|-\n| 09\n| 10 June 1996\n| 29.1\n|-\n| 10\n| 17 June 1996\n| 28.6\n|-\n| 11\n| 24 June 1996\n| 36.7\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://jdorama.com/drama.239.htm JDorama entry]\n* {{IMDb title|0116910|Long Vacation}}\n\n\n[[Category:1996 Japanese television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1996 Japanese television series endings]]\n[[Category:Japanese drama television series]]\n[[Category:Works about pianos and pianists]]\n[[Category:Fuji Television dramas]]\n", "text_old": "{{no footnotes|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = Long Vacation \n| native_name          = {{Infobox name module|kanji=\u30ed\u30f3\u30b0\u30d0\u30b1\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3}}\n| image                = Long vacation.png\n| caption              = Long Vacation title card\n| genre                = Drama, romance\n| camera               = \n| picture_format       = \n| audio_format         = \n| runtime              = \n| creator              = \n| writer               = [[Eriko Kitagawa]]\n| director             = K\u014dz\u014d Nagayama<br/>[[Masayuki Suzuki (director)|Masayuki Suzuki]]<br/>Hirotsugu Usui\n| developer            = \n| producer             = \n| executive_producer   = \n| starring             = [[Takuya Kimura]]<br/>[[Tomoko Yamaguchi]]\n| voices               =\n| narrated             = \n| theme_music_composer = \n| opentheme            = ''[[La La La Love Song]]'' ([[Toshinobu Kubota]]) with [[Naomi Campbell]]\n| composer             = \n| endtheme             =\n| country              = Japan\n| location             = \n| language             = Japanese\n| network              = [[Fuji TV]]\n| first_aired          = 15 April 1996\n| last_aired           = 24 June 1996\n| num_series           = 1\n| num_episodes         = 11\n| list_episodes        = \n| preceded_by          = \n| followed_by          = \n| related              = \n| website              = \n}}\n\n'''''Long Vacation''''' ({{lang|ja|\u30ed\u30f3\u30b0\u30d0\u30b1\u30fc\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3}}, also known as {{lang|ja|\u30ed\u30f3\u30d0\u30b1}}) is a [[Japanese television drama]] series from [[Fuji Television]], first shown in Japan from 15 April to 24 June 1996. [[Takuya Kimura]] and [[Tomoko Yamaguchi]] played the lead characters. The series enjoyed high ratings and was the earliest of a series of hit productions starring Kimura. It features music by [[Cagnet (band)|Cagnet]]. The theme song was ''[[La La La Love Song]]'' by [[Toshinobu Kubota]] with [[Naomi Campbell]].\n\n==Summary==\n\nMinami and Sena meet when Sena's apartment-mate, Asakura, jilts Minami on their wedding day.  Minami learns from Sena that Asakura has left, whereabouts unknown.  Sena allows Minami to move into the apartment, since she is penniless, having given all her money to Asakura, and cannot pay the rent on her apartment.\n\nThis is the beginning of a romance between Sena and Minami. Minami and Sena confide in and console each other about their relationship problems and their lack of success in life.\n\nMinami meets a professional photographer, Sugisaki, who proposes marriage. Finally Sena has a chance of winning a piano competition and going to Boston, joining the symphony orchestra.\n\nThe characters in the series have something in common\u2014if not jobless, they can do no better than secure a temporary job. This is a portrayal of a time when Japan was plagued by deep recession, when its people suffered profound depression from constant failure to earn a stable income. The series portrays how relationships are made and broken, and explores how people come to depend on each other for solace.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Takuya Kimura]] as {{nihongo|Sena Hidetoshi|\u702c\u540d\u79c0\u4fca}}\n*[[Tomoko Yamaguchi]] as {{nihongo|Hayama Minami|\u8449\u5c71\u5357}}\n*[[Yutaka Takenouchi]] as {{nihongo|Hayama Shinji|\u8449\u5c71\u771f\u4e8c}}\n*[[Takako Matsu]] as {{nihongo|Okusawa Ryoko|\u5965\u6ca2\u6dbc\u5b50}}\n*[[Izumi Inamori]] as {{nihongo|Koishikawa Momoko|\u5c0f\u77f3\u5ddd\u6843\u5b50}}\n*[[Ry\u014d (actress)|Ry\u014d]] as {{nihongo|Himuro Rumiko|\u6c37\u5ba4\u30eb\u30df\u5b50}}\n*[[Leo Morimoto]] as {{nihongo|Professor Sasaki|\u4f50\u3005\u6728\u6559\u6388}}\n*[[Ry\u014dko Hirosue]] as {{nihongo|Saito Takako|\u6589\u85e4\u8cb4\u5b50}}\n*[[Kosuke Toyohara]] as {{nihongo|Sugisaki Tetsuya|\u6749\u5d0e\u54f2\u4e5f}}\n\n==Characters==\n\n*Hidetoshi Sena (24) \u2013 An ambitious pianist with dreams of the big time. After graduating from music school, he teaches at a children's piano school for a small income. He lives in an apartment with a baby grand piano in the living room. Sena practises for piano competitions throughout the series. Despite his seemingly very adept technical ability and Sasaki's high opinion of Sena's playing, Sena constantly meets with failure. The reason for this becomes clearer as the story unfolds. Momoko calls him \"Ayrton\" because his surname resembles that of former motor-racing world champion [[Ayrton Senna]]. He suffers many harsh remarks from arrogant student Takako, but still helps her in her struggle with life.\n*Minami Hayama (31) \u2013 An independent and uninhibited 30-year-old woman. Once in demand as a fashion model, she now works as a small-time model on increasingly infrequent jobs. She is unlucky in love: Her fianc\u00e9 elopes with a younger woman on their wedding day. Through a series of circumstances, Minami comes to stay in Sena's house. Their deepening relationship is a main thread of the drama.\n*Shinji Hayama \u2013 Minami's younger brother. A loafer and notorious womanizer, he is also a talented pianist who is later revealed to have had a promising piano career. He comes to Tokyo with his girlfriend Rumiko, relying on [[pachinko]] winnings to foot the bill. He later buys a bar and runs it with her.\n*Ryoko Okusawa \u2013 A very talented pianist but shy with a sheltered upbringing. She is a student in the same music school that Sena graduated from and considered a future star. Sena develops a crush on her but she seems indifferent toward him. Shinji briefly seduces her but later leaves her.\n*Momoko Koishikawa \u2013 Minami's junior in the modelling company and a close friend of Minami. Despite her ditzy manner, she sometimes makes insightful observations and offers useful advice.\n*Rumiko Himuro \u2013 Shinji's girlfriend.\n*Professor Sasaki \u2013 Sena's mentor and former professor. He often encourages Sena to enter piano competitions.\n*Takako Saito \u2013 A child prodigy who is taught by Sena for a brief time. Initially, her attitude toward Sena is disrespectful.\n*Tetsuya Sugisaki \u2013 A dashing professional photographer who falls for Minami.\n\n==Ratings==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%;\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" background: #f9f9f9;\n|- align=\"center\"\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Episode\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Date\n! style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Rating (%)\n|-\n| 01\n| 15 April 1996\n| 30.6\n|-\n| 02\n| 22 April 1996\n| 28.3\n|-\n| 03\n| 29 April 1996\n| 29.0\n|-\n| 04\n| 6 May 1996\n| 27.6\n|-\n| 05\n| 13 May 1996\n| 27.9\n|-\n| 06\n| 20 May 1996\n| 25.5\n|-\n| 07\n| 27 May 1996\n| 27.7\n|-\n| 08\n| 3 June 1996\n| 29.9\n|-\n| 09\n| 10 June 1996\n| 29.1\n|-\n| 10\n| 17 June 1996\n| 28.6\n|-\n| 11\n| 24 June 1996\n| 36.7\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://jdorama.com/drama.239.htm JDorama entry]\n* {{IMDb title|0116910|Long Vacation}}\n\n\n[[Category:1996 Japanese television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1996 Japanese television series endings]]\n[[Category:Japanese drama television series]]\n[[Category:Works about pianos and pianists]]\n[[Category:Fuji Television dramas]]\n", "name_user": "Linda Evans L", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Long_Vacation"}
{"title_page": "Yumenoshima Park", "text_new": "{{Infobox park\n| name = Yumenoshima Park\n| photo = Akahata Matsuri 02.jpg\n| photo_width = 250\n| photo_caption = Akahata Festival in the park in 2010\n| type = \n\n| location = [[K\u014dt\u014d|K\u014dt\u014d Ward]], [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]\n| publictransit = [[Shin-Kiba Station]]\n| coords = {{Coord|35.6493854|N|139.8258119|E|source:placeopedia|display=title}}\n| area = {{convert|433,212|m2|acre}}\n| created = 1 October 1978}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Yumenoshima Park'''|\u5922\u306e\u5cf6\u516c\u5712|Yumenoshima K\u014den}} is a sports park in [[Yumenoshima]], [[K\u014dt\u014d|K\u014dt\u014d Ward]], [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]. It was made by improving a landfill site called Yumenoshima, which had been the final disposal site for garbage from 1957 until 1967. Yumenoshima will be the site of the archery event of the [[2020 Summer Olympics|Tokyo Olympic Games]] in 2020.\n\n==Facilities==\n* [[Yumenoshima Stadium]] containing sports facilities such as a [[track and field]] area\n* Barbecue area\n* Tokyo Sports Culture Center (nicknamed BumB)\n* Yumenoshima Tropical Greenhouse Dome, a [[botanical garden]]\n* Tokyo Metropolitan [[Daigo Fukury\u016b Maru]] Exhibition Hall\n\n==Admission fee==\nAdmission to the park is free of charge, but the Tropical Greenhouse Dome and sports facilities require a fee.\n\n==Opening times and holidays==\nThe park is open all year round. However, the barbecue area is closed on New Year's holidays while the Tropical Greenhouse Dome and Daigo Fukury\u016b Maru Exhibition Hall are closed on New Year's holidays and Mondays.\n\n==Festival==\nThe Akahata Matsuri [[:ja:\u8d64\u65d7\u307e\u3064\u308a]] (literally, Red Flag Festival) is sometimes held in the park. Organised by the [[Japanese Communist Party]], it takes place once every four years or so and lasts about 2 or 3 days. The most recent one was in November 2014.\n\n==2020 Olympics==\nThe Yumenoshima Park is set to be the venue for archery events in the [[2020 Summer Olympics|2020 Tokyo Olympics]]. It will also host archery for the 2020 Paralympics.  The qualification field was completed in February 2019.  A test event for the Olympic and Paralympic Games archery events will be held in July 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.city.koto.lg.jp/seikatsu/sports/82606/84085/file/kyougizyou_map.pdf |title=\u30aa\u30ea\u30f3\u30d4\u30c3\u30af\u30fb\u30d1\u30e9\u30ea\u30f3\u30d4\u30c3\u30af\u7af6\u6280\u5834\u30de\u30c3\u30d7 |accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=170px heights=130px>\nFile: Yumenoshima Tropical Greenhouse Dome.jpg|Yumenoshima Tropical Greenhouse Dome\nFile: Daigo Fukury\u016b Maru 02.JPG|Daigo Fukury\u016b Maru Exhibition Hall\nFile: Kouto Yumenosima feeld.JPG|Looking at the pitch from the stands in the park\nFile: Akahata Matsuri 03.jpg|West entrance to the park during the Akahata Festival in 2010\nFile:Yumenoshima park koto tokyo summer 2014.jpg|Inside the park, 2014\n</gallery>\n\n==Access==\n*Two minutes' walk from [[Shin-Kiba Station]] on the [[Tokyo Metro Y\u016brakuch\u014d Line]], [[Keiy\u014d Line]] and [[Rinkai Line]].\n*Three city buses ([[Toei Bus]]) stop at the park.\n*There are also two parking lots; one on the south side has space for 352 vehicles while another on the north side can hold 103.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Parks and gardens in Tokyo]]\n* [[List of national parks of Japan|National Parks of Japan]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* [http://www.yumenoshima.jp/index.html]\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.tokyo-park.or.jp/park/format/index042.html]\n\n{{2020 Summer Olympic venues}}\n{{Olympic venues archery}}\n\n[[Category:Venues of the 2020 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic archery venues]]\n[[Category:Parks and gardens in Tokyo]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox park\n| name = Yumenoshima Park\n| photo = Akahata Matsuri 02.jpg\n| photo_width = 250\n| photo_caption = Akahata Festival in the park in 2010\n| type = \n\n| location = [[K\u014dt\u014d|K\u014dt\u014d Ward]], [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]\n| publictransit = [[Shin-Kiba Station]]\n| coords = {{Coord|35.6493854|N|139.8258119|E|source:placeopedia|display=title}}\n| area = {{convert|433,212|m2|acre}}\n| created = 1 October 1978}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Yumenoshima Park'''|\u5922\u306e\u5cf6\u516c\u5712|Yumenoshima K\u014den}} is a sports park in [[Yumenoshima]], [[K\u014dt\u014d|K\u014dt\u014d Ward]], [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]. It was made by improving a landfill site called Yumenoshima, which had been the final disposal site for garbage from 1957 until 1967. Yumenoshima will be the site of the archery event of the [[2020 Summer Olympics|Tokyo Olympic Games]] in 2020.\n\n==Facilities==\n* [[Yumenoshima Stadium]] containing sports facilities such as a [[track and field]] area\n* Barbecue area\n* Tokyo Sports Culture Center (nicknamed BumB)\n* Yumenoshima Tropical Greenhouse Dome, a [[botanical garden]]\n* Tokyo Metropolitan [[Daigo Fukury\u016b Maru]] Exhibition Hall\n\n==Admission fee==\nAdmission to the park is free of charge, but the Tropical Greenhouse Dome and sports facilities require a fee.\n\n==Opening times and holidays==\nThe park is open all year round. However, the barbecue area is closed on New Year's holidays while the Tropical Greenhouse Dome and Daigo Fukury\u016b Maru Exhibition Hall are closed on New Year's holidays and Mondays.\n\n==Festival==\nThe Akahata Matsuri [[:ja:\u8d64\u65d7\u307e\u3064\u308a]] (literally, Red Flag Festival) is sometimes held in the park. Organised by the [[Japanese Communist Party]], it takes place once every four years or so and lasts about 2 or 3 days. The most recent one was in November 2014.\n\n==2020 Olympics==\nThe Yumenoshima Park is set to be the venue for archery events in the [[2020 Summer Olympics|2020 Tokyo Olympics]]. It will also host archery for the 2020 Paralympics.  The qualification field was completed in February 2019.  A test event for the Olympic and Paralympic Games archery events will be held in July 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.city.koto.lg.jp/seikatsu/sports/82606/84085/file/kyougizyou_map.pdf |title=\u30aa\u30ea\u30f3\u30d4\u30c3\u30af\u30fb\u30d1\u30e9\u30ea\u30f3\u30d4\u30c3\u30af\u7af6\u6280\u5834\u30de\u30c3\u30d7 |accessdate=19 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery widths=170px heights=130px>\nFile: Yumenoshima Tropical Greenhouse Dome.jpg|Yumenoshima Tropical Greenhouse Dome\nFile: Daigo Fukury\u016b Maru 02.JPG|Daigo Fukury\u016b Maru Exhibition Hall\nFile: Kouto Yumenosima feeld.JPG|Looking at the pitch from the stands in the park\nFile: Akahata Matsuri 03.jpg|West entrance to the park during the Akahata Festival in 2010\n</gallery>\n\n==Access==\n*Two minutes' walk from [[Shin-Kiba Station]] on the [[Tokyo Metro Y\u016brakuch\u014d Line]], [[Keiy\u014d Line]] and [[Rinkai Line]].\n*Three city buses ([[Toei Bus]]) stop at the park.\n*There are also two parking lots; one on the south side has space for 352 vehicles while another on the north side can hold 103.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Parks and gardens in Tokyo]]\n* [[List of national parks of Japan|National Parks of Japan]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* [http://www.yumenoshima.jp/index.html]\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.tokyo-park.or.jp/park/format/index042.html]\n\n{{2020 Summer Olympic venues}}\n{{Olympic venues archery}}\n\n[[Category:Venues of the 2020 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic archery venues]]\n[[Category:Parks and gardens in Tokyo]]\n", "name_user": "Nesnad", "label": "safe", "comment": "image of what inside the park actually looks like", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yumenoshima_Park"}
{"title_page": "Minecraft servers", "text_new": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=Minecraft server|2=Talk:Minecraft servers#Requested move 3 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{short description|Game servers for Minecraft}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=January 2020}}\n'''''Minecraft'' servers''' are player-owned or business-owned multiplayer [[game server]]s within the 2011 [[Mojang]] video game ''[[Minecraft]]''. Players can start their own server using a hosting provider. ''Minecraft'' multiplayer servers are guided by server operators, who have access to server commands such as setting the time of day and teleporting players. Operators can also set up restrictions concerning which usernames or [[IP address]]es are allowed or disallowed to enter the server.<ref name=\"multiplayerservers\">{{Cite web |url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2012/09/blocks-with-friends-how-to-run-your-own-minecraft-server/ |title=Blocks with friends: How to run your own Minecraft server |last=Hutchinson |first=Lee |date=September 10, 2012 |website=[[Ars Technica]] |pages=1\u20134 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121115100732/http://arstechnica.com/gaming/2012/09/blocks-with-friends-how-to-run-your-own-minecraft-server/ |archive-date=15 November 2012 |access-date=19 August 2019 |department=Gaming & Culture}}</ref> Multiplayer servers have a wide range of activities, with some servers having their own unique rules and customs. [[Player versus player]] combat (PvP) can be enabled to allow fighting between players. Many servers have custom plugins that allow actions that are not normally possible in the [[Vanilla software|vanilla]] form of the game. The largest and most popular server is [[Hypixel]], which has been visited by over 14 million unique players.<ref name=\"variety\">{{Cite news |url=https://variety.com/2018/gaming/news/hypixel-studios-reveals-hytale-1203089201/ |title=Creators of Popular 'Minecraft' Server Announce New Game 'Hytale' |last=Fogel |first=Stefanie |date=December 13, 2018 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |access-date=December 15, 2018 |department=Gaming}}</ref><ref name=\"riotgames\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/riot-games-leads-investment-hypixel-game-studio-1168889 |title=Riot Games Leads Investment in Hypixel Game Studio |last=Jarvey |first=Natalie |date=December 13, 2018 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=December 14, 2018 |department=Tech}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nMultiplayer was first added to ''Minecraft'' on May 31, 2009, during the [[Minecraft#Development|Classic]] phase of the game.<ref name=\"gamepedia\">{{Cite web |url=https://minecraft.gamepedia.com/Java_Edition_Classic_0.0.15a_(Multiplayer_Test_1) |title=Java Edition Classic 0.0.15a (Multiplayer Test 1) |website=Official Minecraft Wiki |access-date=January 27, 2020}}</ref>{{better source needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nIn 2013, Mojang announced ''Minecraft Realms'', a server hosting service intended to enable players to run server multiplayer games easily and safely without having to set up their own.<ref name=\"polygonrealms\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.polygon.com/2013/3/18/4118526/minecraft-realms-hopes-to-make-an-increasingly-complex-game-more |title=Minecraft Realms hopes to make an increasingly complex game more family-friendly |last=Crecente |first=Brian |date=March 18, 2013 |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |access-date=March 26, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/minecraft/minecraft-realms-subscription-service-families-will-bring-more-money-game-itself |title=Minecraft Realms is a subscription service for families that will \"bring in more money than the game itself\" |last=Peel |first=Jeremy |date=March 14, 2013 |work=[[PCGamesN]] |access-date=December 2, 2019}}</ref> Unlike a standard server, only invited players can join Realms servers, and these servers do not use IP addresses. At [[Electronic Entertainment Expo 2016]], it was announced that Realms would enable ''Minecraft'' to support [[cross-platform play]] between [[Windows 10]], [[iOS]], and [[Android (system)|Android]] platforms starting in June 2016,<ref name=\"polygonplatform\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.polygon.com/e3/2016/6/13/11922908/minecraft-cross-platform-e3-2016 |title=Minecraft gets cross-platform play later this year |last=Frank |first=Allegra |date=June 13, 2016 |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |access-date=June 13, 2016}}</ref> with other platforms releasing over the next two years.\n\nIn June 2014, Mojang modified the [[End-user license agreement|EULA]] of the computer versions of the game to prevent servers from selling [[microtransactions]] that unfairly affected gameplay,<ref name=\"rps\" /> such as [[pay-to-win]] items,<ref name=\"polygonnotch\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.polygon.com/2014/6/18/5819274/mojang-multiplayer-servers |title=Why some fans are battling with Notch over Minecraft changes |last=Campbell |first=Colin |date=June 18, 2014 |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |access-date=January 26, 2020 |language=en}}</ref> only allowing servers to sell cosmetic items.<ref name=\"eula\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.pcgamer.com/why-minecrafts-new-eula-is-good-for-the-community/ |title=Why Minecraft's new EULA is good for the game |last=Savage |first=Phil |date=June 18, 2014 |work=[[PC Gamer]] |access-date=January 27, 2020}}</ref> Many servers shut down due to this.<ref name=\"kotaku\">{{Cite news |url=https://kotaku.com/the-uncertain-future-of-minecrafts-independent-servers-1790360981 |title=The Uncertain Future of Minecraft's Independent Servers |last=Guthrie |first=Robert |date=December 21, 2016 |work=[[Kotaku]] |access-date=December 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn September 20, 2017, the ''Better Together Update'' was released for ''Bedrock'' editions of the game, which added multiplayer servers, along with four official featured servers: [[Mineplex]], Lifeboat, Cubecraft, and InPVP.<ref name=\"techcrunch\">{{Cite news |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/06/11/minecraft-is-now-available-for-cross-play-on-any-device/ |title=Minecraft is now available for cross-play on any device |last=Shieber |first=Johnathan |date=June 11, 2017 |work=[[TechCrunch]] |access-date=January 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Management==\nManaging a ''Minecraft'' server can be a full-time job for many server owners. Several large servers employ a staff of developers, managers, and artists.<ref name=kotaku/> As of 2014, the Shotbow server employed three full-time and five part-time employees. According to Matt Sundberg, the server's owner, \"large server networks are incredibly expensive to run and are very time consuming.\"<ref name=\"kotaku2\">{{Cite news |url=https://kotaku.com/why-people-are-mad-about-minecrafts-new-changes-1592190004 |title=Why People Are Mad About Minecraft's New Changes |last=Marinconz |first=Steve |date=June 17, 2014 |work=[[Kotaku]] |access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref> According to Chad Dunbar, the founder of ''MCGamer'', \"it really costs to run networks above 1000 concurrent players.\" This includes salaries, hardware, bandwidth, and DDoS protection,<ref name=rps/> and so monthly expenses can cost thousands of dollars.<ref name=kotaku/> Dunbar stated that ''MCGamer'', which has had over 50,000 daily players, has expenses that can be \"well into the five-figure marks\" per month. As of 2015, monthly expenses of ''Hypixel'', the largest server, are nearly $100,000 dollars a month.<ref name=rps/> Many servers sell in-game ranks and cosmetics to pay for its expenses.<ref name=kotaku/><ref name=rps/>\n\n== Popularity ==\nThe most popular ''[[Java Edition]]'' server is Hypixel, which, released in April 2013, has had over 14 million unique players,<ref name=variety/><ref name=riotgames/> around half of all players of the ''Java Edition'' itself.<ref name=\"neowin\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.neowin.net/news/minecraft-java-edition-on-pc-has-now-sold-over-30-million-copies/ |title=Minecraft Java Edition on PC has now sold over 30 million copies |last=Ariyasinghe |first=Pulasthi |date=April 3, 2019 |work=[[Neowin]] |access-date=January 27, 2020 |department=Microsoft}}</ref> Other popular servers include MCGamer, released in April 2012, which has over 3.5 million unique players;<ref name=\"rockpapershotgun\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2015/09/15/minecraft-biggest-servers/ |title=The Future Of Minecraft's Biggest Servers |last=Wiltshire |first=Alex |date=September 15, 2015 |website=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]}}</ref> Wynncraft, released in April 2013, which has over 1 million unique players;<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.techtimes.com/articles/207952/20170522/a-game-within-a-game-wynncraft-is-an-mmorpg-inside-minecraft.htm |title=A Game Within A Game: 'Wynncraft' Is An MMORPG Inside 'Minecraft' |last=Velasco |first=Carl |date=May 22, 2017 |website=Tech Times |department=Culture}}</ref> and Emenbee, released in 2011, which also has over 1 million unique players.<ref name=\"emenbee\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2019-03-23-in-game-tributes-to-minecraft-server-owner-who-died-of-cancer |title=Minecraft players write touching tributes on in-game signs for \"amazing\" server owner who died of cancer |last=Yin-Poole |first=Wesley |date=March 23, 2019 |work=[[Eurogamer]] |access-date=September 28, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"emenbee2\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.pcgamer.com/minecraft-players-build-touching-memorial-to-server-owner-who-died-of-cancer/ |title=Minecraft players build touching tribute to server owner who died of cancer |last=Horti |first=Samuel |date=March 24, 2019 |work=[[PC Gamer]] |access-date=December 5, 2019 |department=News}}</ref> As of 2014, servers such as [[Mineplex]], Hypixel, Shotbow and HiveMC receive \"well over a million unique users every month\", according to ''[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]''.<ref name=\"polygonnotch\" />\n\n==Notable servers==\n===2b2t===\n{{Main|2b2t}}\n[[2b2t]], founded in late 2010, is one of the oldest running servers,<ref name=\"independent\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/features/there-s-alternative-minecraft-server-without-any-rules-gaming-tech-a7323201.html |title=There's an alternative Minecraft server without any rules |last=Kiberd |first=Roisin |date=September 23, 2016 |work=[[The Independent]] |access-date=September 20, 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014042318/https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/features/there-s-alternative-minecraft-server-without-any-rules-gaming-tech-a7323201.html |archive-date=October 14, 2019 |department=Indy/Life}}</ref><ref name=\"newsweek\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.newsweek.com/2016/09/23/minecraft-anarchy-server-2b2t-will-kill-you-498946.html |title=The Minecraft Server That Will Kill You 1,000 Times |last=Kiberd |first=Roisin |date=September 15, 2016 |work=[[Newsweek]] |access-date=September 9, 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014024243/https://www.newsweek.com/2016/09/23/minecraft-anarchy-server-2b2t-will-kill-you-498946.html |archive-date=October 14, 2019}}</ref> whose map is also one of the longest-running unaltered server maps in the game.<ref name=\"vice\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/xywekq/the-worst-place-in-minecraft |title=The Worst Place in Minecraft |last=Paul |first=Andrew |date=October 5, 2015 |work=[[Vice Media|Vice]] |access-date=September 9, 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014214406/https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/xywekq/the-worst-place-in-minecraft |archive-date=October 14, 2019}}</ref> The server is known as an anarchy server, which, defined by Katherine Apostolacus in ''Analogies of Religious Violence in Minecraft'', is a server with \"scarce or no server-wide rules.\"<ref name=\"analogies\">{{Cite journal |last=Apostolacus |first=Katherine |date=December 12, 2016 |title=Analogies of Religious Violence in Minecraft: A Case Study of 2b2t |url=https://www.academia.edu/34446985 |url-status=live |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191124220659/https://www.academia.edu/34446985/Analogies_of_Religious_Violence_in_Minecraft |archive-date=November 28, 2019 |access-date=December 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Hypixel===\n{{Main|Hypixel}}\nHypixel, ''Minecraft''{{'s}} most popular server, was founded in April 2013 by Simon Collins-Laflamme and Philippe Touchette.<ref name=\"rps\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2018/12/20/hytale-is-a-minecraft-follow-up-that-remembers-the-minigames/ |title=Hytale is a Minecraft follow-up that remembers the minigames |last=Macgregor |first=Jodie |date=December 20, 2018 |work=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]] |access-date=December 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Mineplex===\n{{Main|Mineplex}}\nMineplex was founded on January 24, 2013,<ref name=\"oldest\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.oldest.org/entertainment/minecraft-servers/ |title=7 Oldest Minecraft Servers |date=February 22, 2018 |website=oldest.org |access-date=December 18, 2018 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> and is one of four servers officially partnered with Mojang.<ref name=\"polygon\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.polygon.com/e3/2017/6/11/15771190/minecraft-servers-cross-platform-e3-2017 |title=Minecraft is going totally cross-platform |last=Campbell |first=Colin |date=June 11, 2017 |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |access-date=December 1, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"gamereactor\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.gamereactor.eu/news/542833/Mojang+to+partner+up+with+popular+Minecraft+servers/ |title=Mojang to partner up with popular Minecraft servers |last=James |first=Ford |date=June 11, 2017 |work=[[Gamereactor]] |department=News}}</ref> The [[Dallas Mavericks]] partnered with the server in 2016 to create a [[minigame]], ''Dallas Mavericks World'', on the server, which released in the summer of 2016.<ref name=\"geekwire\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.geekwire.com/2016/mark-cuban-minecraft/ |title=Mark Cuban calls Minecraft 'intellectually engaging' as his NBA team creates new game with Mineplex |last=Schlosser |first=Kurt |date=May 24, 2016 |work=[[GeekWire]]}}</ref><ref name=\"alistdaily\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.alistdaily.com/digital/mark-cuban-explains-mavericks-mashing-minecraft/ |title=Mark Cuban Explains Why The Mavericks Are Mashing Up With 'Minecraft' |last=Akopyan |first=Manouk |date=May 1, 2016 |work=AListDaily |access-date=September 22, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"startelegram\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.star-telegram.com/sports/nba/dallas-mavericks/article78613322.html |title=Dallas Mavericks joining computer games world in Minecraft |last=Humphrey |first=David |date=May 19, 2016 |work=[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]]}}</ref><ref name=\"mavs\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.mavs.com/dallas-mavs-partner-minecraft-server-engage-new-generation-basketball-fans/ |title=Dallas Mavs Partner With Minecraft Server to Engage a new Generation of Basketball Fans |last=Wermuth |first=Adam |date=May 18, 2016 |work=[[Dallas Mavericks]] |access-date=January 12, 2020 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171206022939/https://www.mavs.com/dallas-mavs-partner-minecraft-server-engage-new-generation-basketball-fans/ |archive-date=December 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===The Uncensored Library===\n{{Main|The Uncensored Library}}\nThe Uncensored Library is a ''Minecraft'' server and map released in 2020 by [[Reporters Without Borders]] and is an attempt to circumvent [[censorship]] in countries lacking [[freedom of the press]].\n\n===Vatican City server===\nIn 2019, Catholic priest and technology podcaster [[Robert Ballecer]] started an organized religious ''Minecraft'' server to provide a less toxic gaming environment for [[Vatican City]]. The server was immediately subject to [[DDoS]] attacks.<ref name=\"businsider\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/minecraft-server-for-vatican-hit-possible-ddos-attack-priest-says-2019-12 |title=The Vatican started a 'Minecraft' server and it was immediately attacked, according to the priest that set it up |last=Meisenzahl |first=Mary |date=December 5, 2019 |work=[[Business Insider]] |access-date=December 14, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"pcgamer\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.pcgamer.com/the-vatican-has-its-own-minecraft-server/ |title=The Vatican's Minecraft server is overwhelmed by demand and DDoS attacks |last=Macgregor |first=Jody |date=December 3, 2019 |work=[[PC Gamer]] |access-date=December 14, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"metro\">{{Cite news |url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/12/04/minecraft-trolls-target-vatican-server-ddos-attacks-11267238/ |title=Minecraft trolls target Vatican server with DDoS attacks |date=December 4, 2019 |work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |access-date=December 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Minecraft}}\n\n[[Category:Minecraft servers| ]]\n", "text_old": "<noinclude>{{User:RMCD bot/subject notice|1=Minecraft server|2=Talk:Minecraft servers#Requested move 3 April 2020 }}\n</noinclude>{{short description|Game servers for Minecraft}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=January 2020}}\n'''''Minecraft'' servers''' are player-owned or business-owned multiplayer [[game server]]s within the 2011 [[Mojang]] video game ''[[Minecraft]]''. Players can start their own server using a hosting provider. ''Minecraft'' multiplayer servers are guided by server operators, who have access to server commands such as setting the time of day and teleporting players. Operators can also set up restrictions concerning which usernames or [[IP address]]es are allowed or disallowed to enter the server.<ref name=\"multiplayerservers\">{{Cite web |url=https://arstechnica.com/gaming/2012/09/blocks-with-friends-how-to-run-your-own-minecraft-server/ |title=Blocks with friends: How to run your own Minecraft server |last=Hutchinson |first=Lee |date=September 10, 2012 |website=[[Ars Technica]] |pages=1\u20134 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121115100732/http://arstechnica.com/gaming/2012/09/blocks-with-friends-how-to-run-your-own-minecraft-server/ |archive-date=15 November 2012 |access-date=19 August 2019 |department=Gaming & Culture}}</ref> Multiplayer servers have a wide range of activities, with some servers having their own unique rules and customs. [[Player versus player]] combat (PvP) can be enabled to allow fighting between players. Many servers have custom plugins that allow actions that are not normally possible in the [[Vanilla software|vanilla]] form of the game. The largest and most popular server is [[Hypixel]], which has been visited by over 14 million unique players.<ref name=\"variety\">{{Cite news |url=https://variety.com/2018/gaming/news/hypixel-studios-reveals-hytale-1203089201/ |title=Creators of Popular 'Minecraft' Server Announce New Game 'Hytale' |last=Fogel |first=Stefanie |date=December 13, 2018 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |access-date=December 15, 2018 |department=Gaming}}</ref><ref name=\"riotgames\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/riot-games-leads-investment-hypixel-game-studio-1168889 |title=Riot Games Leads Investment in Hypixel Game Studio |last=Jarvey |first=Natalie |date=December 13, 2018 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |access-date=December 14, 2018 |department=Tech}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nMultiplayer was first added to ''Minecraft'' on May 31, 2009, during the [[Minecraft#Development|Classic]] phase of the game.<ref name=\"gamepedia\">{{Cite web |url=https://minecraft.gamepedia.com/Java_Edition_Classic_0.0.15a_(Multiplayer_Test_1) |title=Java Edition Classic 0.0.15a (Multiplayer Test 1) |website=Official Minecraft Wiki |access-date=January 27, 2020}}</ref>{{better source needed|date=January 2020}}\n\nIn 2013, Mojang announced ''Minecraft Realms'', a server hosting service intended to enable players to run server multiplayer games easily and safely without having to set up their own.<ref name=\"polygonrealms\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.polygon.com/2013/3/18/4118526/minecraft-realms-hopes-to-make-an-increasingly-complex-game-more |title=Minecraft Realms hopes to make an increasingly complex game more family-friendly |last=Crecente |first=Brian |date=March 18, 2013 |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |access-date=March 26, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/minecraft/minecraft-realms-subscription-service-families-will-bring-more-money-game-itself |title=Minecraft Realms is a subscription service for families that will \"bring in more money than the game itself\" |last=Peel |first=Jeremy |date=March 14, 2013 |work=[[PCGamesN]] |access-date=December 2, 2019}}</ref> Unlike a standard server, only invited players can join Realms servers, and these servers do not use IP addresses. At [[Electronic Entertainment Expo 2016]], it was announced that Realms would enable ''Minecraft'' to support [[cross-platform play]] between [[Windows 10]], [[iOS]], and [[Android (system)|Android]] platforms starting in June 2016,<ref name=\"polygonplatform\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.polygon.com/e3/2016/6/13/11922908/minecraft-cross-platform-e3-2016 |title=Minecraft gets cross-platform play later this year |last=Frank |first=Allegra |date=June 13, 2016 |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |access-date=June 13, 2016}}</ref> with other platforms releasing over the next two years.\n\nIn June 2014, Mojang modified the [[End-user license agreement|EULA]] of the computer versions of the game to prevent servers from selling [[microtransactions]] that unfairly affected gameplay,<ref name=\"rps\" /> such as [[pay-to-win]] items,<ref name=\"polygonnotch\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.polygon.com/2014/6/18/5819274/mojang-multiplayer-servers |title=Why some fans are battling with Notch over Minecraft changes |last=Campbell |first=Colin |date=June 18, 2014 |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |access-date=January 26, 2020 |language=en}}</ref> only allowing servers to sell cosmetic items.<ref name=\"eula\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.pcgamer.com/why-minecrafts-new-eula-is-good-for-the-community/ |title=Why Minecraft's new EULA is good for the game |last=Savage |first=Phil |date=June 18, 2014 |work=[[PC Gamer]] |access-date=January 27, 2020}}</ref> Many servers shut down due to this.<ref name=\"kotaku\">{{Cite news |url=https://kotaku.com/the-uncertain-future-of-minecrafts-independent-servers-1790360981 |title=The Uncertain Future of Minecraft's Independent Servers |last=Guthrie |first=Robert |date=December 21, 2016 |work=[[Kotaku]] |access-date=December 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn September 20, 2017, the ''Better Together Update'' was released for ''Bedrock'' editions of the game, which added multiplayer servers, along with four official featured servers: [[Mineplex]], Lifeboat, Cubecraft, and InPVP.<ref name=\"techcrunch\">{{Cite news |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/06/11/minecraft-is-now-available-for-cross-play-on-any-device/ |title=Minecraft is now available for cross-play on any device |last=Shieber |first=Johnathan |date=June 11, 2017 |work=[[TechCrunch]] |access-date=January 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Management==\nManaging a ''Minecraft'' server can be a full-time job for many server owners. Several large servers employ a staff of developers, managers, and artists.<ref name=kotaku/> As of 2014, the Shotbow server employed three full-time and five part-time employees. According to Matt Sundberg, the server's owner, \"large server networks are incredibly expensive to run and are very time consuming.\"<ref name=\"kotaku2\">{{Cite news |url=https://kotaku.com/why-people-are-mad-about-minecrafts-new-changes-1592190004 |title=Why People Are Mad About Minecraft's New Changes |last=Marinconz |first=Steve |date=June 17, 2014 |work=[[Kotaku]] |access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref> According to Chad Dunbar, the founder of ''MCGamer'', \"it really costs to run networks above 1000 concurrent players.\" This includes salaries, hardware, bandwidth, and DDoS protection,<ref name=rps/> and so monthly expenses can cost thousands of dollars.<ref name=kotaku/> Dunbar stated that ''MCGamer'', which has had over 50,000 daily players, has expenses that can be \"well into the five-figure marks\" per month. As of 2015, monthly expenses of ''Hypixel'', the largest server, are nearly $100,000 dollars a month.<ref name=rps/> Many servers sell in-game ranks and cosmetics to pay for its expenses.<ref name=kotaku/><ref name=rps/>\n\n== Popularity ==\nThe most popular ''[[Java Edition]]'' server is Hypixel, which, released in April 2013, has had over 14 million unique players,<ref name=variety/><ref name=riotgames/> around half of all players of the ''Java Edition'' itself.<ref name=\"neowin\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.neowin.net/news/minecraft-java-edition-on-pc-has-now-sold-over-30-million-copies/ |title=Minecraft Java Edition on PC has now sold over 30 million copies |last=Ariyasinghe |first=Pulasthi |date=April 3, 2019 |work=[[Neowin]] |access-date=January 27, 2020 |department=Microsoft}}</ref> Other popular servers include MCGamer, released in April 2012, which has over 3.5 million unique players;<ref name=\"rockpapershotgun\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2015/09/15/minecraft-biggest-servers/ |title=The Future Of Minecraft's Biggest Servers |last=Wiltshire |first=Alex |date=September 15, 2015 |website=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]]}}</ref> Wynncraft, released in April 2013, which has over 1 million unique players;<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.techtimes.com/articles/207952/20170522/a-game-within-a-game-wynncraft-is-an-mmorpg-inside-minecraft.htm |title=A Game Within A Game: 'Wynncraft' Is An MMORPG Inside 'Minecraft' |last=Velasco |first=Carl |date=May 22, 2017 |website=Tech Times |department=Culture}}</ref> and Emenbee, released in 2011, which also has over 1 million unique players.<ref name=\"emenbee\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2019-03-23-in-game-tributes-to-minecraft-server-owner-who-died-of-cancer |title=Minecraft players write touching tributes on in-game signs for \"amazing\" server owner who died of cancer |last=Yin-Poole |first=Wesley |date=March 23, 2019 |work=[[Eurogamer]] |access-date=September 28, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"emenbee2\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.pcgamer.com/minecraft-players-build-touching-memorial-to-server-owner-who-died-of-cancer/ |title=Minecraft players build touching tribute to server owner who died of cancer |last=Horti |first=Samuel |date=March 24, 2019 |work=[[PC Gamer]] |access-date=December 5, 2019 |department=News}}</ref> As of 2014, servers such as [[Mineplex]], Hypixel, Shotbow and HiveMC receive \"well over a million unique users every month\", according to ''[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]''.<ref name=\"polygonnotch\" />\n\n==Notable servers==\n===2b2t===\n{{Main|2b2t}}\n[[2b2t]], founded in late 2010, is one of the oldest running servers,<ref name=\"independent\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/features/there-s-alternative-minecraft-server-without-any-rules-gaming-tech-a7323201.html |title=There's an alternative Minecraft server without any rules |last=Kiberd |first=Roisin |date=September 23, 2016 |work=[[The Independent]] |access-date=September 20, 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014042318/https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/features/there-s-alternative-minecraft-server-without-any-rules-gaming-tech-a7323201.html |archive-date=October 14, 2019 |department=Indy/Life}}</ref><ref name=\"newsweek\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.newsweek.com/2016/09/23/minecraft-anarchy-server-2b2t-will-kill-you-498946.html |title=The Minecraft Server That Will Kill You 1,000 Times |last=Kiberd |first=Roisin |date=September 15, 2016 |work=[[Newsweek]] |access-date=September 9, 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014024243/https://www.newsweek.com/2016/09/23/minecraft-anarchy-server-2b2t-will-kill-you-498946.html |archive-date=October 14, 2019}}</ref> whose map is also one of the longest-running unaltered maps in the game.<ref name=\"vice\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/xywekq/the-worst-place-in-minecraft |title=The Worst Place in Minecraft |last=Paul |first=Andrew |date=October 5, 2015 |work=[[Vice Media|Vice]] |access-date=September 9, 2019 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191014214406/https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/xywekq/the-worst-place-in-minecraft |archive-date=October 14, 2019}}</ref> The server is known as an anarchy server, which, defined by Katherine Apostolacus in ''Analogies of Religious Violence in Minecraft'', is a server with \"scarce or no server-wide rules.\"<ref name=\"analogies\">{{Cite journal |last=Apostolacus |first=Katherine |date=December 12, 2016 |title=Analogies of Religious Violence in Minecraft: A Case Study of 2b2t |url=https://www.academia.edu/34446985 |url-status=live |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191124220659/https://www.academia.edu/34446985/Analogies_of_Religious_Violence_in_Minecraft |archive-date=November 28, 2019 |access-date=December 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Hypixel===\n{{Main|Hypixel}}\nHypixel, ''Minecraft''{{'s}} most popular server, was founded in April 2013 by Simon Collins-Laflamme and Philippe Touchette.<ref name=\"rps\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.rockpapershotgun.com/2018/12/20/hytale-is-a-minecraft-follow-up-that-remembers-the-minigames/ |title=Hytale is a Minecraft follow-up that remembers the minigames |last=Macgregor |first=Jodie |date=December 20, 2018 |work=[[Rock, Paper, Shotgun]] |access-date=December 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Mineplex===\n{{Main|Mineplex}}\nMineplex was founded on January 24, 2013,<ref name=\"oldest\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.oldest.org/entertainment/minecraft-servers/ |title=7 Oldest Minecraft Servers |date=February 22, 2018 |website=oldest.org |access-date=December 18, 2018 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> and is one of four servers officially partnered with Mojang.<ref name=\"polygon\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.polygon.com/e3/2017/6/11/15771190/minecraft-servers-cross-platform-e3-2017 |title=Minecraft is going totally cross-platform |last=Campbell |first=Colin |date=June 11, 2017 |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |access-date=December 1, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"gamereactor\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.gamereactor.eu/news/542833/Mojang+to+partner+up+with+popular+Minecraft+servers/ |title=Mojang to partner up with popular Minecraft servers |last=James |first=Ford |date=June 11, 2017 |work=[[Gamereactor]] |department=News}}</ref> The [[Dallas Mavericks]] partnered with the server in 2016 to create a [[minigame]], ''Dallas Mavericks World'', on the server, which released in the summer of 2016.<ref name=\"geekwire\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.geekwire.com/2016/mark-cuban-minecraft/ |title=Mark Cuban calls Minecraft 'intellectually engaging' as his NBA team creates new game with Mineplex |last=Schlosser |first=Kurt |date=May 24, 2016 |work=[[GeekWire]]}}</ref><ref name=\"alistdaily\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.alistdaily.com/digital/mark-cuban-explains-mavericks-mashing-minecraft/ |title=Mark Cuban Explains Why The Mavericks Are Mashing Up With 'Minecraft' |last=Akopyan |first=Manouk |date=May 1, 2016 |work=AListDaily |access-date=September 22, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"startelegram\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.star-telegram.com/sports/nba/dallas-mavericks/article78613322.html |title=Dallas Mavericks joining computer games world in Minecraft |last=Humphrey |first=David |date=May 19, 2016 |work=[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]]}}</ref><ref name=\"mavs\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.mavs.com/dallas-mavs-partner-minecraft-server-engage-new-generation-basketball-fans/ |title=Dallas Mavs Partner With Minecraft Server to Engage a new Generation of Basketball Fans |last=Wermuth |first=Adam |date=May 18, 2016 |work=[[Dallas Mavericks]] |access-date=January 12, 2020 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171206022939/https://www.mavs.com/dallas-mavs-partner-minecraft-server-engage-new-generation-basketball-fans/ |archive-date=December 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===The Uncensored Library===\n{{Main|The Uncensored Library}}\nThe Uncensored Library is a ''Minecraft'' server and map released in 2020 by [[Reporters Without Borders]] and is an attempt to circumvent [[censorship]] in countries lacking [[freedom of the press]].\n\n===Vatican City server===\nIn 2019, Catholic priest and technology podcaster [[Robert Ballecer]] started an organized religious ''Minecraft'' server to provide a less toxic gaming environment for [[Vatican City]]. The server was immediately subject to [[DDoS]] attacks.<ref name=\"businsider\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/minecraft-server-for-vatican-hit-possible-ddos-attack-priest-says-2019-12 |title=The Vatican started a 'Minecraft' server and it was immediately attacked, according to the priest that set it up |last=Meisenzahl |first=Mary |date=December 5, 2019 |work=[[Business Insider]] |access-date=December 14, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"pcgamer\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.pcgamer.com/the-vatican-has-its-own-minecraft-server/ |title=The Vatican's Minecraft server is overwhelmed by demand and DDoS attacks |last=Macgregor |first=Jody |date=December 3, 2019 |work=[[PC Gamer]] |access-date=December 14, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"metro\">{{Cite news |url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/12/04/minecraft-trolls-target-vatican-server-ddos-attacks-11267238/ |title=Minecraft trolls target Vatican server with DDoS attacks |date=December 4, 2019 |work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |access-date=December 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Minecraft}}\n\n[[Category:Minecraft servers| ]]\n", "name_user": "Melofors", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e2b2t", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minecraft_servers"}
